esforce authentication settings","Salesforce error logs","Default and custom field mappings","Overwriting vs. auto-filling information","And more"]}),(0,a.jsxs)(s.A,{component:"span",children:["Want to learn even more about Apollo's Salesforce integration? Check out the"," ",(0,a.jsx)(h,{href:"https://knowledge.apollo.io/hc/en-us",children:"Knowledge Base"}),"."]})]})},{title:"Apollo Analytics",shortDescription:"Optimize your outbound workflow by getting a bird’s eye view on how your engagement efforts are performing. Create reports using metrics and dimensions, and create custom dashboards.",wistiaId:"o1a2usxfsn",length:"4:56",deepLink:{heading:"Like what you're learning?",url:"https://app.apollo.io/#/login",linkText:"Do it in Apollo",extraPadding:!0},description:(0,a.jsxs)(n.A,{spacing:3,children:[(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{variant:"h5",children:"In this lesson, Josh dives into the world of Apollo's Analytics—where you can gain insights into the performance of your team's engagement efforts so you can optimize their outbound workflow."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"You'll learn how to:"}),(0,a.jsx)(i.A,{color:"purple",items:["Create customized reports, focusing on specific users, timeframes, and engagement metrics","Explore the metrics and dimensions functionalities to analyze hard numbers and slice data for deeper insights","Build customized dashboards—leveraging pre-built templates to analyze email engagement stats, top-performing reps, effective sequences, successful templates, and more"]}),(0,a.jsxs)(s.A,{component:"span",children:["Want to learn more about Apollo's analytics? Check out our"," ",(0,a.jsx)(h,{href:"https://knowledge.apollo.io/hc/en-us",children:"Knowledge Base"}),"."]})]})},{title:"Enriching your CRM",shortDescription:"Keep your contact info up to date by enriching your CRM. Review potential enrichments and schedule data automation.",wistiaId:"n13g12iuix",length:"5:56",deepLink:{heading:"Like what you're learning?",url:"https://app.apollo.io/#/login",linkText:"Do it in Apollo",extraPadding:!0},description:(0,a.jsxs)(n.A,{spacing:3,children:[(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{variant:"h5",children:"Data enrichment is simply a way to keep your CRM (or a CSV—but we'll cover that in the next video) nice and tidy, ensuring your team's contact data is always up to date, actionable, and effective."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"Join Josh as he covers:"}),(0,a.jsx)(i.A,{color:"purple",items:["Enrichment settings you should configure","Why you should have multiple phone number fields set up","How to enable autofill for values your CRM doesn’t have","Scheduling enrichments for job changes or missing email addresses","How to use the Data Health Center to view enrichment activity","And more!"]})]})},{title:"Enriching a CSV",shortDescription:"Keep your contact info up to date by enriching a CSV file. Enrich by people or companies and choose standard fields.",wistiaId:"ywm18160st",length:"2:52",deepLink:{heading:"Like what you're learning?",url:"https://app.apollo.io/#/login",linkText:"Do it in Apollo",extraPadding:!0},description:(0,a.jsxs)(n.A,{spacing:3,children:[(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{variant:"h5",children:"What do you do if your team collects leads from a trade show or webinar that don't quite have all the info they were hoping for? That's where CSV enrichment comes in handy."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"In this short but oh-so-helpful lesson, Josh will spill the beans on how to easily enhance CSV data, edit enrichment settings like a pro, and (bonus) how to manually approve job changes Apollo recommends."})]})},{title:"The Data Health Center",shortDescription:"Easily find your total addressable market and keep an eye on the health and quality of the data in your CRM.",wistiaId:"3zkkm2gmqd",length:"4:21",deepLink:{heading:"Like what you're learning?",url:"https://app.apollo.io/#/login",linkText:"Do it in Apollo",extraPadding:!0},description:(0,a.jsxs)(n.A,{spacing:3,children:[(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{variant:"h5",children:"In this final installment of how to set your teams up for success in Apollo, Josh walks through The Data Health Center—your go-to tool for uncovering your total addressable market and the overall quality of your CRM'S data."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"You'll learn how to:"}),(0,a.jsx)(i.A,{color:"purple",items:["Enable or disable personas on your Data Health Center dashboard","Create account segments (like a persona, but for a company)","Automatically or manually update contacts","Grab valuable insights into your total addressable market via existing CRM data vs. potential net new data","And more!"]}),(0,a.jsxs)(s.A,{component:"span",children:["Ready to put everything you learned in this course into action?"," ",(0,a.jsx)(h,{href:"https://app.apollo.io/#/login",children:"Log in to Apollo"})," ","(or sign up ",(0,a.jsx)(h,{href:"/sign-up",children:"here"}),"!)."]})]})}],b=[{title:"The most important skill",shortDescription:"Discovery isn’t a box to check — it’s the foundation your entire deal is built on.",wistiaId:"6lc5mc6wr0",length:"6:13",deepLink:{color:"purple",heading:"Unlock insights from every discovery call with Apollo AI",linkText:"Sign up for free",url:"/sign-up",extraPadding:!0},description:(0,a.jsxs)(n.A,{spacing:3,children:[(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{variant:"h5",children:"Discovery isn’t a box to check — it’s the foundation your entire deal is built on."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"In this lesson, Chris Orlob breaks down why discovery is the most important skill in sales, and how it shapes everything from your demo to your negotiation strategy."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"You’ll learn what most reps get wrong about discovery (spoiler: those go-to questions might be doing you more harm than good), and why nailing the first 10 minutes of the call can make or break your chances of winning the deal."})]}),transcript:`Ten years ago, my success in sales felt a little… up to chance.

Some months I’d rake in the dough, other months it was back to canned beans for dinner. And I couldn’t figure out why… until I cracked the code to discovery.

As a rookie AE, what I needed was a repeatable discovery system. A way to know exactly what to say to surface my prospects’ needs. 

So I embarked on a quest. 

I read hundreds of sales books. You name it, I read it. 

I analyzed over three thousand of my own discovery calls over the span of six years. 

And what I learned changed everything. 

I was the Director of Sales at Gong, and I’m now the founder and CEO of PClub.io. 

The discovery framework I’m going to teach you is what I used to help grow Gong into a 7.2 billion dollar company.

It’s what I used to build, lead, and train my sales org to a record-breaking number of President’s Club winners.

My discovery methods have helped over 12,000 sellers reach their financial goals, and now it’s your turn.

My name is Chris Orlob, and I’m going to teach you how to master discovery to win more deals.

———

I’m gonna let you in on a secret: if you master every aspect of selling, you can have anything you want.

This is what my mentor told me when I was a twenty-something doe-eyed AE with forty dollars to my name. 

Well I took that to heart, spent thousands of hours studying the art of selling, and now I’m sitting in this chair.  

And I can tell you, that out of all the skills you can master as a seller, discovery is the most important one.

If you’re new to sales, “discovery” is that initial conversation between you and a prospect, and your goal is to uncover their underlying problem, and the cause of that problem, so that you can help solve it. 

The most crucial part of discovery is the first 10 minutes, which is what I’m going to help you master today in this course. Nail the first 10 minutes, and you stand a good chance of winning the deal. Flub it, and you’re not even in consideration. 

You’ve heard the phrase — “you only get one chance at a first impression”. Sales is the same way. If you can uncover what your prospect really cares about… BEFORE giving your pitch, you’ll set yourself up for success — because sales is not about your product. It’s about their problem, and the process of uncovering it. A problem well defined is ninety percent solved, and discovery helps you do that.

Now, why is discovery the most important skill you can develop in sales?

Because discovery influences every. single. part. of your sales process going forward. 

It influences how you run your demo calls, who you loop in throughout the process, how you structure your proof of concept and your business case, and then finally how you negotiate — the positioning you’re going to take and your ability to defend pricing.

So, yeah — discovery matters. Big time.

The funny thing about discovery, though, is that it’s both the most popular and least understood topic in sales. Most SaaS salespeople think they’re nailing it, but if you ask their bosses? Eight out of ten would disagree. 

For example… here are a few discovery questions you might be using on calls that you think are effective, but are actually making your buyers throw up in their mouths. This might sting a little, so grab some ice.

“What keeps you up at night?”

“How does this impact you personally?”

“You’re having trouble with [blank]? Well our tool helps you solve that.”

I cringe when I hear these. I cringe because I’ve been there! So here’s what I’m going to teach you in this course:

I’m going to teach you how to prep for your discovery calls in a way that puts your competitors to shame. 

Then, I’ll teach you how to set the rules of engagement by managing your buyer’s expectations for the meeting

In lesson four and five, I’ll teach you the difference between handling inbound and outbound leads — because failing to do so will make or break your discovery. 

And then finally, I’ll teach you the most important concept in this course: how to uncover the need behind the need — peeling back the surface-level layers of what your prospect says to reveal their deeper, underlying challenge.

By the end of this course, you’ll be equipped with discovery skills that will help you close more deals and build the life you’ve dreamed of.

That’s my goal because… once upon a time I had no intention of being a professional seller, and every intention of being a professional drummer.

I spent six years practicing for hours every day — it was my life… until I got tendinitis in three of my limbs and was told by my doctor I had to give it up. 

To say this depressed me is an understatement. I didn’t know what I was going to do, but I knew I wanted to be successful. I confided in a friend (who to this day has never sold a thing in his life) and he said “If you want to make good money then you should commit to getting very good at selling.”

And that’s what I did. It changed my life, my family’s life, and now I’m passionate about changing yours. 

So if you’re frustrated with deals falling through the cracks; if you’re stressed about hitting your quota; if you’re surprised how hard it is to get buyers to listen during discovery calls… you’re in the right place. 

I’ll help you transform your sales success from chance… to controlled. From inconsistent… to unstoppable. Starting with what to do in the ten minutes before your discovery calls. Let’s dive in.

`},{title:"Prepping like a pro",shortDescription:"Bad discovery calls usually start before the call ever begins.",wistiaId:"hy8hk8hhvv",length:"6:43",deepLink:{color:"purple",heading:"Unlock insights from every discovery call with Apollo AI",linkText:"Sign up for free",url:"/sign-up",extraPadding:!0},description:(0,a.jsxs)(n.A,{spacing:3,children:[(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{variant:"h5",children:"Bad discovery calls usually start before the call ever begins."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"It’s not about having the perfect script — it’s about doing the kind of pre-call prep that builds trust before you even say hello."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"In this lesson, Chris shares the prep strategies that separate top-performing sellers from everyone else."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"You’ll learn:"}),(0,a.jsx)(i.A,{color:"purple",items:["Where most sellers go wrong when researching (and what to do instead)","How to craft “context-led questions” that spark real conversation","The 3 key areas you should pull your insights from","Simple ways to gain permission and avoid tunnel vision","And more!"]})]}),transcript:`Back in my early days as an AE, I was on a discovery call with a CRO and his director of operations. 

Being the overly confident young man that I was, I did nothing to prepare for this call. So naturally, I asked the CRO a couple generic, open-ended questions.… and he kept giving me curt responses. I didn’t even make it through my third question when the CRO said “I don’t have time for a generic call”, and he just… left. Exited the meeting room.  

No amount of therapy could undo the trauma I felt at this moment.

Let’s talk about how you can prepare for discovery calls, so you never make the same trauma-inducing mistakes I did.

———

Trust is the foundation of sales, and building that trust starts with the research you do before a single word is exchanged.

Lucky for you, most sellers (including your competitors) just do this: They check the company website and the prospect’s LinkedIn. Big deal.

But you’re not going to do what most other sellers do. You’re going to do this instead: You’re going to go five layers deeper. You’re going to investigate: What is the company’s business model? How do they make money? What are the threats to the company, and the opportunities? 

Maybe you don't know this in much detail, but you should at least investigate and see if you can develop a point of view.

If you come into calls having done research, you communicate instant credibility. You show your buyer (who honestly is used to hearing a lot of bullcrap) that you genuinely know your stuff and are there to problem solve — not just push a product.

Now, if you’re anything like how I used to be, you can have all this knowledge in your head… but then once you’re actually ON the call, nerves hit and you draw a blank. (That’s okay, even the best sellers in the world have been there). 

Here’s how you can prevent that from happening. You can use what I call context-led questions. These are questions preceded by an observation or insight (usually based on your pre-call research) that give context as to why you’re asking the question. 

In simpler terms: give context first, then ask your question. 

Here’s why that matters: discovery questions often feel like shots in the dark to your buyers. But when you preface them with even just a dash of insight, your buyer feels like you “get it” — and that’s how trust is built.

There are three key areas I’d suggest pulling your insights from: your buyer’s company, the industry in which they operate, and external factors impacting their business. 

You can use information pulled from any of these three areas to prep a few context-led questions prior to your discovery calls.

Here’s an example of what this can look like in the real world, pulling insight from a buyer’s company:

“Jack, if it’s okay with you, I’d love to start by talking about something I read on your company’s recent press release. It mentioned your company is entering the precision manufacturing category and plans on competing in that space going forward. Do you mind if we start by talking about what factors drove the decision to enter that market?”

Sharing an observation before your question gets your buyer far more engaged and likely to have a productive conversation than if you were to just start with “So what drove you into the precision manufacturing space?” 

Here’s another example, this time pulling insight from external factors impacting their business:

“Jill, maybe we can start here? You’re head of sales for a hiring software company. The elephant in the room, as far as I can tell, is your market is hiring significantly less than they were a year ago. How are you handling that and what kind of changes are you considering making to your sales approach?”

Again, we’re leading with a point of view that gets our buyer to open up and expand on the insight we just shared, giving us valuable information in the process.

Now, your context-led questions won’t always hit the mark, right? Like any skill, they take practice. Well, after 10 years in the game, here are three tips I’d recommend when preparing context-led questions .

First, keep them relevant to your problem area. 

I’m stating the obvious here, but if you’re not asking something that ties back to a problem you solve, then you’re just giving away free consulting (Which, hey… power to ya. But you’re not making a sale that way…).  

Second, gain permission. 

Notice how in the examples I shared, I asked permission to shift the conversation’s focus — something to the effect of “If it’s okay with you, I’d like to start here”. This is a great way to grease the wheels, so to speak, and get buy-in on conversations.

Finally, don’t get tunnel vision. 

It can be easy to hyper focus on one point, not realizing your buyer has other priorities. So do a pulse check every now and then with a question like “Is this THE thing we should be talking about, or is there something else on your mind?” This simple question can keep you aligned and prevent tunnel vision syndrome. 

There’s still a lot more I could teach you about prepping for calls, including the three most common mistakes I see sellers make on discovery calls. If you’re curious what those are, I encourage you to head over to Apollo’s YouTube channel and watch what I have to say on this topic there. 

I want to end this lesson by proposing a challenge. I want you to choose an upcoming discovery call, then plan and write down a context-led question you’d like to use.

But that’s not all. After the call, I want you to reflect and self assess. How did it go? Did it seem like you were on or off base? How can you improve for next time? Document what you learn — you can use the worksheet provided in the resources section of this course. 

So now you know how to prep for your calls. But what do you say in those crucial first few minutes of an actual discovery call? We’ll cover that, next…`},{title:"Setting the rules of engagement",shortDescription:"The first five minutes of a discovery call can make or break the entire conversation.",wistiaId:"qz5dkkgu9s",length:"5:06",deepLink:{color:"purple",heading:"Unlock insights from every discovery call with Apollo AI",linkText:"Sign up for free",url:"/sign-up",extraPadding:!0},description:(0,a.jsxs)(n.A,{spacing:3,children:[(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{variant:"h5",children:"The first five minutes of a discovery call can make or break the entire conversation."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"In this lesson, Chris shares the exact talk track he uses to kick off every discovery call. You’ll walk away with a repeatable script you can start applying right away."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"You’ll learn:"}),(0,a.jsx)(i.A,{color:"purple",items:["How to set the “rules of engagement” without sounding robotic or pushy","The 3 areas to align on with your buyer up front","Why the phrase “Does that feel fair?” is your new secret weapon","How to use softening statements to make your buyer feel at ease","And more!"]})]}),transcript:`What you do in the first five minutes of a discovery call can make or break the entire conversation. No pressure.

Luckily, there are things you can do to dramatically reduce your odds of the call going poorly. This is where setting the rules of engagement comes in.

———

Picture this. 

You’re waiting at the doctor’s office — sitting on crinkly exam paper, wearing that paper-thin gown that does absolutely nothing for your self-esteem.

Suddenly, the doctor bursts in with a quick  “hey how are ya?”, then dives right into an exam. No discussion about what’s about to happen, no expectations set — just a flurry of pokes and prods that make you wish you never showed up.

This is how a discovery call can feel for buyers when you don’t lay the proper groundwork: awkward, invasive, maybe even offensive!

You’ve got to earn the right to dig into your buyers' challenges by first setting what I call the rules of engagement. 

Setting the “rules of engagement” simply means creating a clear, mutual understanding between you and the buyer regarding how the rest of the call will proceed. 

While doing this doesn’t guarantee success, it certainly helps. It helps keep your conversations on track — if say, your buyer comes at you with “just show me the product!” or gets annoyed with all your questions; it eliminates buyer friction by establishing a clear framework for the call; and it helps you get to their true pain, faster, by paving the way for a productive conversation.

So what does setting the rules of engagement look like? It looks like managing expectations and getting alignment from your buyer on three things: the objective, the agenda, and the next decision. 

Getting alignment on the objective means establishing the outcome you and your buyer are trying to achieve by the end of the call.

Alignment on the agenda means establishing the line items that will be discussed, in service of the objective.

And then alignment on the ‘next decision’ means establishing what decision you both agree will be made at the end of the call.

Now, this is all fine and dandy, but how do you do this? How do you translate the rules of engagement into a real-life call with actual humans??

Here’s what the first five minutes of your discovery calls should look like:

First: spend the first minute or so on some basic small talk. This is not rocket science — you don’t need to channel your inner-comedian or debate the finer points of philosophy here. But talk about something. I’ve seen one too many salespeople jump right into business, which can feel jarring for your buyer. 

So engage in small talk. Then, once you sense it’s time to switch gears, transition with something to the effect of “Mind if we talk about the agenda?”

Now we get into the rules of engagement. The key to success here is to make your buyer feel like they’re in control of the conversation. We want to give them a sense of autonomy over the rules of engagement. 

You’ll do this by using what I call softening statements, which sound like this: “Here’s what I’m thinking. Let me know if you have a different agenda.”

This helps your buyer feel like they have veto power over your suggestions, and gives them the sense of control in the conversation, even though you’re the one driving it.

Alright. Now you go into explaining how you’re thinking about the call. And that looks like this:

For the objective: “The outcome I recommend we shoot for is…” blank.

For the agenda: “To get there, here’s what I have in mind…”

And for the next decision: “By the end, I’d like to put you in a position where you can decide…” blank.

Keep in mind that the “next decision” is NOT a buying decision, but rather a concrete decision that will either move the deal forward or stop it in its tracks… such as scheduling a next step or parting ways. Setting this expectation at the beginning of the call will give you something to reference at the end when you’re trying to solidify next steps.

Now finally, you’re going to end this talk track with saying “Does that feel fair?”

This is a powerful phrase. Again, it gets the buyer feeling like they’re in control, but also gets them to most likely agree with the agenda you proposed (assuming you put some thought into it).

So there you have it. I’ve given you the blueprint for the first five minutes of your discovery calls. Now I want you to put it all into practice. I want you to plan and write down your rules of engagement for an upcoming call, then reflect and assess what can be improved for next time. To do this, you can use the talk track and the worksheet provided in the resources section of this course.

Otherwise, let’s dive into the heart of discovery — asking the right questions to uncover your buyer’s true challenges. See you in the next lesson.`},{title:"The go-back-in-time technique",shortDescription:"Sometimes your buyer’s ready to skip straight to solution-talk. Other times, they're colder than ice.",wistiaId:"rns6bepr7m",length:"6:03",deepLink:{color:"purple",heading:"Unlock insights from every discovery call with Apollo AI",linkText:"Sign up for free",url:"/sign-up",extraPadding:!0},description:(0,a.jsxs)(n.A,{spacing:3,children:[(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{variant:"h5",children:"Sometimes your buyer’s ready to skip straight to solution-talk. Other times, they're colder than ice."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"In this lesson, Chris shows you how to kickstart discovery the right way — by matching your questions to where your buyer actually is in their journey (not where you wish they were)."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"You’ll learn:"}),(0,a.jsx)(i.A,{color:"purple",items:["How to spot when a buyer is actively exploring vs. in latent pain","Why misaligned questions create friction and how to avoid it","Chris’s exact talk track for uncovering deeper pain points in inbound calls","How to use permission points to build trust","And more!"]})]}),transcript:`Ever find yourself in one of these two scenarios?

The first is you’re on a discovery call with a prospect SO eager to talk about solutions, they have no interest in answering your questions about their core problem.

The second scenario is your classic “cold” buyer who’s so reluctant to open up that doing discovery with them feels like trying to pull teeth.

Two very different scenarios, but here’s the twist — they both stem from the same problem. 

In the next two lessons, I’ll teach you how to craft discovery questions that tackle both scenarios head-on and steer your conversations where they need to go. Let’s dive in.

———

The first thing you should know about kickstarting discovery is that most buyers come from one of two psychological places. 

The first are our “eager beavers” — buyers who are actively exploring. They’ve often come inbound to you, are probably looking at competitors, and they mostly want to talk solutions… not the underlying problem that started it all.

The second are our cats in the bath — buyers with latent pain. You’ve gone outbound to them, so they’re reluctant to do discovery with you… and finding a solution to a problem they haven’t crystallized yet isn’t a huge priority.

In lesson one, I told you that the goal of discovery is to uncover your buyers’ underlying problem or true pain. But in both the scenarios I just presented, your buyer is making that difficult. So what do you do?

Well, in both scenarios, this friction usually happens for the same reason. And that reason is that your discovery is not aligned with where your buyer is in the “buyer’s journey”.

Here’s what I mean. 

If you’re talking to an actively exploring inbound lead who’s currently defining, evaluating, or deciding on a solution and you say “Tell me about your key challenges”, well… they’re already past that.  They’ll get irritated because you’re treating them as if they’re in the first half of the buyer’s journey, when they’re more interested in talking about the second.

The key to discovery is to ask questions that meet your prospect exactly where they are on the buyer’s journey. I’ll show you how to do that. Let’s keep talking about inbound leads for now, and we’ll cover outbound leads in the next lesson. 

Since inbound leads, or our actively exploring leads, are typically interested in talking about solutions, you’re going to use something I call the go-back-in-time technique. 

The go-back-in-time technique means you start by asking a couple questions that align with your buyer’s desire to talk about solutions. THEN, you’ll ask for their permission to “go back in time” and talk about the original pain that set this all in motion.

When this is done tactfully, this demonstrates to your buyer that you understand their desires — and they’re going to be a lot more willing to have a productive conversation with you. When you don’t do this, that’s when you cause friction. 

So what does a go-back-in-time question look and sound like?

Here’s the exact talk track you should use. You can modify this talk track if you’d like, but I’ve found it actually works pretty well across a wide range of categories and markets. 

So after you’ve established your rules of engagement, and you’ve identified your lead as ‘actively exploring’, one of the first questions you can ask is:

“Tell me about what motivated you to look into [your solution category]...” 

This question meets your inbound lead where they are in the buyer’s journey. But one question isn’t enough, right? You’ll probably still kill the vibe if you dive into the past at this point.

So after you’ve had a little back-and-forth about the first question, you can then ask a second question that piggybacks off the first:

“What are you aiming to accomplish with something like this?” 

You could even ask “What are you looking for in a solution like this?” Either way, you’re asking another question that warms them up to you and builds trust.

Now (and only now) that we’ve done that, can you whip out the time machine and ask about pain from the past. And you’ll do it like this:

“Interesting. Can I go back in time with you for a sec? What was the original challenge going on in the business that caused you to prioritize looking for a solution like this?”

Notice something I did here — I asked for their permission. This is something you should get in the habit of doing throughout your sales career. I call these phrases permission points. Remember what we talked about in lesson three. The more you ask leads for buy-in and give them the feeling of control, the more they’ll open up to you and be receptive to what you have to say.

Okay. We just covered how to meet your inbound leads where they are in the buyer’s journey, then how to tactfully pivot the conversation to talk about their underlying pain.

Time to try it on your own.

I want you to choose an upcoming discovery call, then plan and write three ‘go back in time’ questions that follow the script I’ve provided. Then, as always, I want you to self assess and make note of what did or didn’t go well, and why. You can use the worksheet provided with this course to help keep track of your notes. 

Otherwise, let’s shift gears. How do we handle leads with latent pain? The ones who aren’t actively searching for solutions just yet, and aren’t exactly thrilled to hear from you? We’ll talk about them, next.`},{title:"The discovery prompter",shortDescription:"What if there was a way to instantly warm up cold leads in your discovery calls?",wistiaId:"9i90fkksp1",length:"6:44",deepLink:{color:"purple",heading:"Unlock insights from every discovery call with Apollo AI",linkText:"Sign up for free",url:"/sign-up",extraPadding:!0},description:(0,a.jsxs)(n.A,{spacing:3,children:[(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{variant:"h5",children:"What if there was a way to instantly warm up cold leads in your discovery calls?"}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"According to Chris, there is. It’s called the discovery prompter — a storytelling framework that gets your prospects saying things like, “It feels like you’re peering into my soul.”"}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"In this lesson, you’ll learn:"}),(0,a.jsx)(i.A,{color:"purple",items:["The two methods for thawing out cold outbound leads","How to craft mini-stories your prospects can relate to","A simple handoff line that gets buyers talking about their core issues","How to practice this technique so it feels natural","And more!"]})]}),transcript:`“It feels like you’re peering into my soul” — This is what a VP of Sales from a major company once said to me on a discovery call. 

What’s so striking about this statement is that, just moments earlier, this VP was — like many outbound leads — very irritable and ready to write me off. But something I said instantly changed his mood. This man literally let out a sigh of relief then unloaded all his business challenges on me for ten minutes — every seller’s dream!

So.. what was it I said? I used a technique I call the discovery prompter…

———

Before we dive into the ins and outs of the discovery prompter, let’s quickly review who we’re talking about here. 

In the last lesson, we learned about inbound leads who are actively exploring solutions. Now we’re talking about outbound leads — buyers with latent pain. They’re experiencing challenges or inefficiencies but aren’t fully aware of them or don’t see the need for a solution yet. So they often drag their feet, expecting you to push a product they don’t think they need. 

These leads are at the beginning of the buyer's journey, so you’ll need to align your discovery accordingly. Just imagine being in their shoes and getting hit with, “So what motivated you to look into this solution?”. They’re gonna get irritated and go from cold to freezing fast.

Our goal with outbound leads is to thaw them out, so to speak, with the least amount of friction as possible. And there are a couple different ways we can do that. 

The first should sound familiar — it’s our context-led-questions, aka questions preceded by an observation or insight (usually based on pre-call research) that give context as to why you’re asking the question. I’ll let you rewatch lesson two if you need a refresher, but context-led questions work great for thawing out cold leads because they build your credibility and set the stage for a productive conversation.

The second technique you can use to warm up outbound leads is what I call the discovery prompter.

The discovery prompter is something you can use at the beginning of your discovery call right after you’ve set the rules of engagement. And it starts with you telling a short, pain-based narrative your buyer can see themselves in, then ‘passing the torch’ back to your buyer. 

Now, this is going to require some storytelling skills. You want to tell a story in a way that makes your buyer go “hey, that’s exactly what I struggle with too!” When done right, this technique should open the floodgates for your buyers to start talking about their challenges. 

If you’re NOT a storyteller by nature, don’t fret. I’ve already done half the work for you. Based on my experience, here’s what the structure of your discovery prompter should look like:

“One of the customers we worked with was dealing with…” (insert pain statement)

“Before working with us, they were struggling with…” (expand on the customer’s pain)

“In fact, it was such a struggle that…”(describe negative ramifications)

“The short story is we helped them…” (achieve desired future state)

And then you end by passing the torch.

“But enough about our customers… tell me about the key challenges YOU are facing when it comes to…” (your area).

At this point — as long as you’ve done your job telling a story that resonates — your buyer will start giving you a wealth of information about the challenges they’re facing.

Here’s something worth noting. I want you to sear this into your seller’s brain — one of the quickest and most effective ways to earn a buyer’s trust is to articulate their problem better than they can themselves, and the discovery prompter helps you do that.

Let’s look at an example. Let’s say you’re talking to a healthcare organization that’s struggling with patient retention. You might say something like…

“I personally worked with a hospital system similar to yours that was facing challenges in keeping patients engaged with follow-up care after discharge.”

“Before working with us, their patient retention rates for post-treatment care had dropped significantly, causing readmissions to spike.”

“It was becoming such a problem that patient satisfaction scores were plummeting, and administrative costs for follow-up care were rising fast.”

“The short story is we helped them implement a more streamlined follow-up process that not only increased retention but reduced readmission rates by 30%.'

(Now the hand off.)

'But enough about our customers… tell me about the key challenges YOU are facing when it comes to patient care that would become problematic if left unresolved in the next 6-12 months…”

Notice something I did there at the end. I said “...if you didn’t solve them 6-12 months out.” This phrase works wonders in getting people to zero in on their most urgent problems. 

Also, keep in mind that this example is probably a shortened version of a story I would actually tell. In reality, you’ll probably expand on some points and weave in elements to make the story more engaging and relatable. Don’t be afraid to talk for a few minutes, probably four or five minutes max. As long as you follow the basic discovery prompter structure, you should strike a chord. 

Don’t get too discouraged when the discovery prompter doesn’t go amazingly well the first few times you use it. Even the best sellers in the world don’t get these things right immediately. The key is to practice, practice, practice. I promise it’ll get easier as you go.

Speaking of practice… let’s get into your sales mastery challenge. 

I want you to choose an upcoming discovery call you have with a cold lead and choose a customer story you think will resonate with them. Follow the discovery prompter framework, write it down, then practice it out loud at least three times before your call. Then try it live, and self-assess. And of course, you can use the worksheet provided in the resources section below.

In the meantime, let’s move on to the MOST important lesson you can watch in this course: uncovering the need behind the need. See you there.`},{title:"Uncovering the need behind the need",shortDescription:"You can uncover a big problem, promise a massive ROI…and still lose the deal. Why? Because you didn’t discover the need behind the need.",wistiaId:"1j0k4n4wqp",length:"7:39",deepLink:{color:"purple",heading:(0,a.jsxs)("div",{className:"flex max-w-[350px] flex-col",children:[(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{variant:"captionMonoLarge",children:"next"}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{variant:"h4",children:'Watch "How to Use AI-Powered Call Recording"'})]}),linkText:"Go to course",url:"/academy/learn/how-to-use-ai-powered-call-recording",extraPadding:!0},description:(0,a.jsxs)(n.A,{spacing:3,children:[(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{variant:"h5",children:"You can uncover a big problem, promise a massive ROI…and still lose the deal. Why? Because you didn’t discover the need behind the need."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"In this final lesson, Chris teaches you the #1 skill that separates top sellers from everyone else: uncovering the real, underlying pain that decision-makers are actually willing to spend money on."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"You’ll learn:"}),(0,a.jsx)(i.A,{color:"purple",items:["Why even “good” discovery often isn’t enough","How to peel back the layers of surface-level pain to find business-critical problems","The 3 signs you’ve hit the real need behind the need","A simple (but powerful) way to dig deeper","And more!"]})]}),transcript:`I once had an enterprise SaaS seller say to me after losing a deal, “Chris, I don’t get it. I got all the executives to agree I could save them a million dollars — 10x return — and they STILL said ‘Talk to us in six months’. What gives?!”

This seller was baffled. And maybe you’ve been there before too.

The reason he lost the deal — and why you might be losing deals you shouldn’t — is what I’m going to teach you in this lesson. It’s all about “uncovering the need behind the need”... 

———

I would argue that what I’m about to teach you is the most important key to cracking the discovery code. 

Until you master this concept, sales can feel like a coin toss — one moment you land a win, and the next you lose a deal you thought was a slam dunk. What works for one buyer doesn’t work for another, and it all feels a bit unpredictable and up to chance.

But what if I told you it doesn’t have to be that way. There’s a way to better predict outcomes and take control of the process. 

That’s where uncovering the need behind the need comes in.

Decision-makers live in time and attention poverty. Only the most pressing, business-critical problems will get their attention… and cash.

So any time you’re having a discovery conversation with a potential buyer, imagine they throw an onion at you, and your job is to peel back the layers of the onion until you get to the core of the problem… aka the business pain that money follows… aka the need behind the need. 

Where most sellers go wrong in their discovery is they stop at the first sign of pain — usually a surface-level issue. And guess what? Surface-level problems only get you surface-level deals… or no deals at all!

Now, a common question I get asked at this point is, “How do I know when I’ve uncovered the core — THE business problem?”

There are two attributes to look for:

First is it should be a problem you can actually solve. No duh, right? You may uncover a high-priority problem, but it doesn’t matter much if you can’t solve it.

And the second is that it should be top priority with decision makers. If they don’t agree that the problem you’ve uncovered is a fire worth putting out, you’re not getting a deal.

So when uncovering the need behind the need, make sure it’s a problem you can actually solve AND that it’s a top priority with the right people.

To do that, it’s going to require a concerted effort on your part. Because like I said, buyers are prone to giving surface-level answers at the start of discovery sessions. Fortunately, there’s a tool you can use to peel back those layers. It’s a tool my seven-year-old daughter is familiar with — it’s asking the question “why”. But unlike my daughter, we’re going to ask “why” without literally asking “why”. We’re going to ask some variation of the following question:

“What challenge is going on in your business that’s driving that to be a priority?”

This is when you’ll find that buyers either chuckle or sigh, because they’re thinking of the core issue that’s going on in the business. 

Let’s take a look at an example of what this can look like. This is a real discovery call I had with one of my reps at Gong. 

We were talking to a sales enablement manager and the SVP of Sales and Services, and I asked “What motivated you to look into Gong?”

The sales enablement manager answered with “We need visibility into our sales conversations.”

Alright, fine. But how much money do you think someone would spend to solve the problem of “visibility” alone? Not much, right? That’s a surface-level issue.

So, we peeled back the onion and asked “What’s driving you to crave visibility into your sales conversations?” and he said “Well, our reps are struggling to sell to power, so we need to coach them up on that.”

I then asked, “What’s driving that desire to coach?”

He said, “As a result of poor power selling skills, our sales cycle is nine months but we think it should be six.”

Bingo. Now we’re really starting to get somewhere. But we’re still not deep enough. 

I asked “I’m sure there’s a lot of opportunities in your business right now, but you’ve chosen to focus here. What’s going on that’s driving you to focus resources on this sales cycle issue?”

At this point, the SVP jumps in, which is a really good sign, and she says “Well, a nine-month sales cycle means we have an eleven-month cash cycle. That puts our cash position at risk, especially when you forecast two years out. If we don’t reduce our cash cycle, we’ll need to raise more capital and it will be highly dilutive.”

Ding, ding, ding! We’ve just uncovered a massive pain: a potential cash crisis that could cost the company millions. That’s a problem worth spending money on, but we wouldn’t have known that if we didn’t keep peeling the onion. This is why we keep asking “why”.  And in this example, how did we know we hit THE business problem? One, because Gong can certainly help solve this problem by decreasing the sales cycle. And two, because it’s a top priority with a decision maker — the SVP of Sales and Services.

This leads me to my final point: you’ll know you’ve peeled the onion deep enough when the issues you’re discussing involve a suffering metric that your decision maker owns. If you’re talking to a VP of sales, for example, that might be ‘closed rates’. If you’re selling to a Chief Marketing Officer, it might be ‘rate of pipeline generation’. Keep an ear out for whatever that metric is that’s suffering and owned by a decision maker, and you’ll know you’ve hit the core. 

—-

Now… we’ve covered a LOT in this course. And there’s a LOT more I could teach you. If you’re interested in learning where to take your discovery calls from here, visit PClub.io, where I cover this topic and others in more depth.

Remember — this is all going to take practice… maybe a LOT of practice! But the results are worth it. I’ve taught over 12,000 sellers how to earn an extra $50 to $100k in annual income, and YOU are next on the list. Your success isn’t years away, it’s skills away. 

I’m Chris Orlob, thank you for watching my course, and I wish you the best of luck on your discovery journey.`}],k=[{title:"The goal of cold emails",wistiaId:"b3a26b0owk",length:"1:50",description:(0,a.jsxs)("div",{className:"space-y-6",children:[(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"Sending effective cold emails starts with understanding their true purpose."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"It’s not to establish value. It’s not even to book a meeting."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"So what is it? Join James as he sets the stage for cold emailing—what your goal should be, common challenges you’ll face in trying to break into inboxes, and why relevance is mission critical."})]}),deepLink:{heading:"Find and close your next deal in Apollo",url:"/sign-up",linkText:"Sign up for free"},transcript:`In this course, we're going to cover how to send great cold emails using Apollo.

What's the goal of a cold email? Is it to establish value, book a meeting, or get the recipient to buy right away by sending over their credit card information?

It's none of those things. The goal of a cold email is to start a relationship. And to do that, you need to get a reply. Fifty-nine percent of companies say cold email is their most reliable lead generation channel, and there's good reason for it.

It's cost-effective and efficient. You get wide reach, can touch a lot of leads, and it sets up all your other outbound selling activities. But it's getting harder. The reply rate is now down to around three percent on average. Forty-nine percent of emails are now labeled as spam. And, of course, Google, Yahoo, and other email providers are always looking for ways to clean up their users' inboxes.

So what do we do? Well, cold emails are sent to people who don't know us. They don't know our company or how our product can help them. So we've got to be relevant. Prospects want something that speaks to what they're dealing with in their life or business, and you achieve that by personalizing your emails. 

That's what this course is about. I'm going to show you how to find great, targeted leads worthy of putting time into so you can research them, customize, and create great personalized cold emails. Then, we'll tie it all together with sequences so you can secure as many meetings as possible through follow-ups.

By the end of this course, you'll be ready to send great cold emails that resonate with your prospects. Join me in the next video, where I'll show you how to find great leads inside of Apollo and ensure your lead list is clean.
`},{title:"Finding ideal leads",wistiaId:"xpvwa8ueke",length:"6:00",description:(0,a.jsxs)("div",{className:"space-y-6",children:[(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"Before sending that first email, you need to build a high-quality lead list tailored to your needs."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"Shooting from the hip (i.e. mass blasts) is a guaranteed way to kill your pipeline. Let James teach you a much better, more targeted approach."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"This lesson covers how to:"}),(0,a.jsx)(i.A,{color:"purple",items:["Use Apollo’s powerful search filters to find your perfect leads","Ensure clean data with accurate email addresses","Save searches for easy access","Set up automatic alerts for new leads","Save contacts","And more!"]})]}),deepLink:{heading:"Like what you're learning?",url:"https://app.apollo.io/#/login",linkText:"Do it in Apollo"},transcript:`In this video, we're gonna cover finding great targeted leads in Apollo.

We'll use the search filters to really hone in and find our perfect leads. Then, we'll use email status to ensure we have clean data and accurate email addresses for our cold email campaign. Next, we'll save our search and turn on alerts so that Apollo surfaces more of these great leads for us automatically. Finally, I'll show you how to save your contacts, ensuring you get their work email, work phone number, and even their mobile phone number.

Follow along inside your Apollo account. Do it with me, and if you need more time, pause the video.

Let's go do it.

So here we are at the Apollo home screen. Let's click on ‘Search’ and find some great leads. Apollo has sixty-five filters.

There's a lot of different ways to hone in. I'm gonna show you some of the ones I like to use. And for this example, I'm selling software that helps make salespeople more productive. I also wanna meet with executives.

So I'm gonna go to ‘job titles’, and I'm gonna put in ‘CEO’, ‘President’, and ‘Founder’.

You‘ll notice that you can include management level here.  There's also department and job functions. That's really popular. If you just wanna talk to anybody in a certain department, hit the plus sign and you can choose a more granular job type right there. 

The next thing I'm gonna go to is location.

I'll sell anywhere basically, but I want to send emails now where it could potentially allow me to meet with them in person. So I live in Chicago. I'm gonna put Chicago right here, greater Chicago area. And I'm doing that under ‘Contact’. Now, if you care about where the company's based out of, just like with ‘job title’, you can put in multiple (whether that be city, state, country, or ZIP code) right here.

The next one I'm gonna go to is ‘Number of employees’.

Now my sweet spot, if I'm looking for my VIP, my best possible leads, is 100 to 1,000. But put whatever is good for you here. And if it doesn't matter, you don't need to put anything.

The next one I'm gonna go to is ‘Industry & Keywords’ just to highlight it. I don't care for my business, but many people do. ‘Industry & Keywords’ is just like job title where you can put in multiple — accounting, financial services — and then you'll only see leads within those verticals.

I'm gonna go up to this ‘More filters’ button, and you'll see all the rest of the sixty five filters pop out. I'm looking for one that I intend to use a lot moving forward. So you'll notice a little gray tack shows up on any of these other filters here. I can hit that, and now it moves to my pin filters on the left.

I'm putting in number of employees by department. Again, if I'm selling software for salespeople, I might wanna make sure that they have a sales team. So I'm gonna choose sales and put in ten.

That'll make sure I'm only looking gonna choose sales and put in ten. That'll make sure I'm only looking at executives that work at companies where they’ve got at least ten people on their sales department.

I'll hit apply filters and you'll notice that with all of my filters on, I've narrowed things down from around 300 million contacts in Apollo to 12,000. That's still more than I can effectively work, but it's really, really targeted. 

Now we're gonna go to email status. You'll see it right here. And when you click that open, there's gonna be two green options, ‘likely to engage’ and ‘verified’. Let's select those because, again, we're sending cold emails. We wanna make sure we’ve got accurate email addresses. We don't wanna be getting a lot of bounced emails — that'll be bad for our email deliverability.

You'll notice at the top, there's total, net new, and saved. If you ever want to use Apollo Search to filter through your saved leads, you can go right here. And when you're searching, if you only want to see contacts you haven't yet worked (leads you haven't saved), you go to net new.

Again, pause the video if you need more time. I want you to apply all the filters that will allow you to get really targeted for your business. Once you start seeing leads that look good, you'll notice that you can click into any of them and hit the access email and phone number, big blue button. You click that, and it'll save it to your account.

It'll get their work email and their work phone number. If you wanna get the mobile as well, just click ‘request mobile number’. If there's one available, that'll save to that lead in your account as well. 

Now if you'd like to save in bulk, you can just go down the side and check the boxes next to the names you like, or you can do it the way I do. I like to select a page of twenty five or fifty and hit the ‘save’ button right here. 

A couple things to note is that you can go down to this mobile numbers tab. Just hit the plus, and you can check this box once as it goes through and saves them. If there's mobile numbers available, it'll attach it to all accounts where it's there. It'll charge your credit only if it finds one.

Once you get your leads saved, the ones we're gonna send cold emails to, let's save this search. There's probably more leads here you're gonna wanna come back to. I'm gonna hit ‘save search’ at the bottom of the filters right there, and let's title this something that gives us an understanding of what this search was for. Give yourself clarity at a glance. These are my best possible leads. So I could put ‘VIP executives in Chicagoland with sales teams.’ 

You can make it public or private if you wanna share it internally. I'm gonna pin it to the sidebar for easy access. 

And then the most important thing here to note is that there's something called ‘search subscription alerts’. You can set them for daily, weekly, monthly, or you can have it off. Now if your search is for something where there's not a lot of people, you might want it to be daily so you find out within 24 hours. On mine, I'm just gonna set it to monthly because there's still so many more leads here I have to prospect.

I'm gonna save that search, and you'll notice that right next to Search right here, there's a ‘save search’ tab. When you click on that, you'll see your search. 

In the next video, I'm gonna show you how to get great leads from anywhere on the Internet, including company sites and LinkedIn.
`},{title:"Using the Chrome extension",wistiaId:"yag3kaao4s",length:"4:10",description:(0,a.jsxs)("div",{className:"space-y-6",children:[(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"To personalize your emails, you need to research your prospects. To research your prospects, you should be using Apollo’s Chrome extension."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"In this lesson, James walks through how to research leads and find accurate and verified emails wherever you are online, including LinkedIn."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"This lesson covers how to:"}),(0,a.jsx)(i.A,{color:"purple",items:["Install and set up the Chrome extension","Research and save leads directly from LinkedIn or company websites","Quickly save contact info","Add leads to sequences from wherever you are","And more!"]})]}),deepLink:{heading:"Ready to give Apollo’s Chrome extension a go?",linkText:"Download it free",url:"https://chromewebstore.google.com/detail/apolloio-free-b2b-phone-n/alhgpfoeiimagjlnfekdhkjlkiomcapa"},transcript:`In this video, I'm gonna show you how to use Apollo's Chrome extension to find and research leads.

We're gonna use the Apollo Chrome extension to find leads, research them, and have all those details available to us when we're sending our emails, and we're gonna do it on the Internet, including LinkedIn. Again, follow along. Pause if you need more time. Let's get to it.

Before you can use the Apollo Chrome extension, you're gonna need to add it to your Chrome. So click the link in the resource kit. It'll take you to this page. As you'll see, it's got lots of users, great ratings, and that's because it helps so much with prospecting or researching leads anywhere on the Internet. So go add this to your Chrome now. Pause if you need more time so you can copy along as I show you some of the ways to use it on LinkedIn.

Once you've got it installed, you'll be able to use this anywhere on LinkedIn, and there's a lot of ways to use it. For example, you can quickly save new leads from people who comment on your posts or your company posts, competitors' posts, or groups within LinkedIn. 

So I recently saw that some folks had commented on one of my posts. When I click on their name, you'll notice that this Apollo logo is always on the sidebar here. When you click that, it'll pop up this individual in the Apollo database, and you can save their contact into your account with all their contact information. If you wanna get their mobile number, you can do that right from here as well. ‘Request mobile’. If it's available, it'll charge you the mobile credit and add it to the account.

Now this one looks like it could be an okay fit, but I'd like to find one that's even better. One way to do that is by just searching on LinkedIn using your search terms or searching through all your connections you already have to see if there's somebody there that fits something you might be looking for. For example, in this search, I'll choose this person because they're a chief customer officer. I'm selling sales software. This would probably be in their purview.

I can click the ‘A’ right here, save that contact. It's going back to my Apollo account and it looks like it would be a good fit.

So I could add them directly to my sequence from this screen. I'm gonna add them to my VIP lead sequence, and that looks good.

Now, if you just can't wait, you can actually dial using your Apollo Dialer directly from the widget.

[ James makes the call ]

“The person you are trying to reach is unavailable. Leave your message at the tone.”

I'm gonna send them an email in a few moments.

In addition to being able to save contacts and call from here, it's also a great place to put your research. You'll notice under activities, you can log any notes you might find. So I'm gonna scroll down and I like to see what people have been posting about. If there's anything there that I can use when I'm crafting an email or calling again later.

And I'm noticing here that this individual has been interviewed, so I'm gonna grab that link and save it into my notes for this lead.

Now that'll be in my Apollo account. It'll be patched to this lead in my sequence, and I'll have something to go on when I'm putting together that first email. 

You can also use the Apollo Chrome extension on company websites, which can make prospecting when you don't have much to go on a lot easier. 

So, for example, I'm on a company website here. I hit the Apollo ‘A’ and it'll pop up the company details. If it looks interesting, something that you wanna prospect from, you can hit save company and now it will be saved back in your Apollo account. You can also just click employees right here and see all the different contacts we have associated with this company back in the database. If one of them looks interesting, you might wanna prospect them, you could hit access email, and you'll notice even from here, you can add to a sequence as well.

So as you can see, the Apollo Chrome extension really helps for prospecting or researching your leads anywhere on the Internet. In the next video, I'm gonna show you how to build a sequence, and I'm gonna tell you the secret to maximizing the number of meetings you can get. See you there.
`},{title:"Building sequences",wistiaId:"lojova0haa",length:"7:41",description:(0,a.jsxs)("div",{className:"space-y-6",children:[(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"Now that you’ve identified and researched your dream team of leads, it’s time to map out your comms gameplan. That’s where sequences come in."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"You’re more likely to book a meeting with a sequence vs. a single email… 3x more likely, in fact."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"In this lesson, James demonstrates how to utilize the power of sequences to turn leads into replies."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"You’ll learn how to:"}),(0,a.jsx)(i.A,{color:"purple",items:["Add leads to a sequence","Set up a recommended five-step sequence for high-value leads","Create manual & automatic emails with personalized templates","Utilize dynamic variables","And more!"]})]}),deepLink:{heading:"Like what you're learning?",url:"https://app.apollo.io/#/login",linkText:"Do it in Apollo"},transcript:`In this video, I'm going to show you how to maximize the number of replies you're getting and how many meetings you're booking by using sequences. Now a sequence is your way of telling Apollo your game plan. What activity do you want to do for a certain basket of leads, whether that be making a phone call or sending an email? 

The folks that don't use them have the worst odds of success. Just using a sequence of automated emails, kind of the worst way to use them, you're 3x-ing the odds of booking a meeting. And if you're willing to follow-up multiple times and diversify that follow-up, making calls or sending a note or whatever it might be, then you have the best odds of success. 

That's what we're going to do in this video. I'm going to show you how to add new leads to a sequence. We're going to set up a five-step sequence that's great for your VIP, your best leads, and then we're going to set it up so that we're sending a customized personalized email right off the bat. So follow along with me, get this set up in your Apollo account. If you need more time, pause the video.

At the home screen, we're going to click on 'sequences' on the sidebar right here on the navigation bar, and it'll take you to this screen where you can just hit 'new sequence', and we're going to create one from scratch. Now, just like with our saved search, we want to title this something that tells us what should go in here. A good rule of thumb is whatever you name a search, name the sequence the same thing. So ‘VIP leads Chicago executives’. Now I know what leads go into what sequence. They're named the same thing.

We're going to hit 'add a step', and you'll see all these different options of what a salesperson might want to do with a lead, whether that be sending an email or a phone call. We're going to start with manual email. The difference with the manual email is that it won't go out automatically, but it gives the opportunity to maybe personalize it some more, add some details. You can still get most of it done with a template.

I'm going to mark this as high priority, and here we are at the ‘edit template’ screen. Now if you’ve got an email you already like to use or you want to type one fresh, just a couple quick notes. At the bottom, you'll see there's a little button that says 'add dynamic variables'.

All these codes, when you put them into an email, Apollo will fill in that detail for you. So if you put, ‘Hi, first name’ in the email when it goes out, it'll already be updated to be that person's first name.

If you don't have an email that you like, go into the resource kit right now, pause this, and copy over that one. We put in examples for every step of this sequence. I'm going to grab that right now.

I've updated it a little bit from the resource kit, and I'm going to pop it right in. And you'll notice that it's all showing up in my preview window on the right here. You can always choose one of your saved leads to see how it would look like going to your prospect.

Now mine is showing up with a little bit of red here. You'll notice it says ‘personalized intro’, and it's all highlighted red. You can put in a little note to yourself like that. When it's not a real variable, it won't let the email go out. It's considered a broken variable. That's my reminder and also my way to make sure that it doesn't go out by accident. Hit 'save as a new template' at the bottom. Pop it in, ‘Exec email 1’, and now you'll have easy access to that moving forward, and we've got our first step in. 

The second one will be automated. Let's hit 'add a step' and then select 'automatic email'.

You'll notice that at the top of your ‘edit template’ screen, there's a little box to check that says 'reply to previous thread'. Let's check that, and you'll see the first email you send is showing up in the preview window. 

Now I've got this saved, but you can grab it from the resource kit, a simple one-line reply that gives you a second chance with that first email you sent. In this case, it's just: “Hey, first name. A quick yes or no is fine. Do you need help with…?” And then whatever you're talking about in your email. For me, that's sales, and I'll hit 'save'.

And now I've got my second step of the sequence done, and, again, that one's going to go out automatically if they don't respond yes or no to the first email. 

The third step we're going to add is a phone call. Now on this one, if you want to give yourself the script for your phone call or your voicemail, you can pop it into the notes field here, and you could even use the dynamic variables.You can kind of dummy proof it for yourself so that your script actually says the person's name or company name or whatever you want to be in there. But once you hit 'continue', that'll be in here. And if you're on the Pro or Custom plan with the built-in Dialer, then it's really easy. You can be dialing from Apollo and have the script right next to it. 

The fourth step we're going to add is a LinkedIn connection request. You'll see it right here. The first screen has a notes field. That's just for yourself. On the second screen, you'll see there's 'send connection request message'. This is where you can leave it blank, but if you want to send something, you could pop it in here and still use the variables. So I'm going to put in: “Hey, first name. Would love to be connected with update on your endeavors. Regards, James”.

'Save changes', and now that'll go out and update with their real first name whenever I'm executing that task. And on the last one, we're going to add one more automatic email. Again, if you have something of your own you want to use or write something fresh, great. But if you go to the resource kit, we've got a great example for this third email. I'm going to copy that as well, and it's just a shorter retouch to rephrasing of some of the value in the first one and trying to get somebody's attention a little bit by saying that you're not going to be reaching out. It's called the “breakup” email. So I'm going to paste that in here, put in the subject line, and hit 'save'.

So now you'll have a five-step sequence with diversified follow-ups ready to go. Any leads that go in here will start with step one, move to two, three, and so on, unless they reply to one of your emails or you take them out because on the phone call step, somebody picks up and says, “Absolutely. I have to buy.” 

Now there's no contacts in here, though. We're going to go back to our search. We've got our saved search, and let's grab twenty-five contacts from there.

And you'll notice right here, you can actually save and move into a sequence all at once. So when you're going to go put your first leads into the sequence, it might say ‘inactive’. That's okay. You probably prefer that because you don't want anything to happen until the leads are in there. You double check things and we turn it on. So I'm moving my twenty-five leads. If we want the mobile numbers, don't forget to hit this plus sign next to the mobile numbers and check this box. That way, it'll download the mobile numbers where available and pop it into the records there in your account. So we'll hit 'save'.

You'll notice at the top it says 'in progress', it's adding my twenty-five contacts, it saved them. We can go back to the sequence and you'll notice it's now got twenty-five contacts. It's in pause. It's ready to go.

When your sequence is all ready, just hit this little toggle right here. It'll turn to ‘active’, and all your tasks will start queuing up from the sequence. Not only on your sequence right here, but on your home screen and on the task menu as well. 

We've got one more bonus video for you. We get to watch me work. I'm going to show you how to tie it all together, everything you've learned in this course so you can constantly be booking meetings. See you in the next video.
`},{title:"Connecting the dots",wistiaId:"qe5setem79",length:"7:23",description:(0,a.jsxs)("div",{className:"space-y-6",children:[(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"Join James as he takes us on a journey through a day on the sales floor as a cold emailer."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"You’ve learned the ins and outs of emailing from Apollo: how to find targeted leads, research them, and add them to a multi-channel sequence."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"Now watch as James ties it all together, executes on tasks, and gives you a feel for what a streamlined workflow in Apollo can look like for you."})]}),deepLink:{heading:"Like what you're learning?",url:"https://app.apollo.io/#/login",linkText:"Do it in Apollo"},transcript:`This video, it's going to be a little bit different. We're coworkers. We're both sitting on the sales floor, and I'm going to show you how to tie everything together that we just learned in this course from search and prospecting on LinkedIn with the Chrome extension, making sure our sequence is set up perfectly and sending our great cold emails.

The goal being, we want to book constant meetings, and I have to do that for my job. So let's do it together. I'm going to hop into Apollo. Let's go book some meetings.

So here we are. We're at my Apollo home screen. But before I do anything here, I'm going to go to my calendar, and I'm going to add one more thing. I just added a sequence task block every day for my afternoon for one hour.

I'm going to add a prospecting block every day in the morning because if you want to continually be booking meetings, that means you gotta be adding new leads to your sequence, researching them, and also doing all the tasks that come every day from your sequences. So I've got an hour in the morning for prospecting, an hour in the afternoon for my sequence tasks. And that's going to allow me to have success now, but also in the future.

So I'm going to go to my sequence and show you. I walked you through how to set one up. I've actually got a real one here. It's a little bit different just because there's more phone calls in here.

And I've got my template in the first one that I need to customize.

But before we do anything here, I want to do some more prospecting. That's my morning block. That's what you'll be doing when you're prospecting as well. So the easiest ways to do that are one — we've got our saved search. So I'm going to go back to that and load up my saved search and grab another twenty five leads. Every day, I'll grab twenty five, add them to the sequence, and over time, we're going to keep researching them to do that first email.

So you can add it right from here, 'sequence', this will save them and put them into the sequence at the same time.

And again, if you want the mobile numbers, hit the 'plus' next to mobile numbers and check that box. We're going to hit 'save'.

I've got twenty five prospects now going to my sequence and they'll be starting off at step one.

So now I've got eighty eight there. I also like to go prospect on LinkedIn using the Chrome extension.

So I'm going to go over to my LinkedIn, and there's a couple ways to do this. You have your own network that you can prospect from so if you haven't done that yet, I'm going to click on 'my network', go to 'connections' and then you can sort this. So 'search with filters', 'all filters', I'll go on 'first connections' and I might look for folks that previously worked at the same company as me. So let's do Career Builder.

You'll notice when you have that Chrome extension, there's some Apollo stuff here because you can start pulling multiple contacts and hitting 'save' in bulk, putting them into your Apollo account. You can also go to individuals’ pages and a great way to do this is folks who comment on your post or your company post, competitors post, or I'm looking for sales leaders. 

So I'm going to search for sales, go to 'groups', and then if you're part of a group already or you search for one that might be a good fit for the type of leads you're looking for, let's go to Sales Pro Central.

Oftentimes, you can see the members. In this one, I can only see connections I already have, but these might be a great fit. This would be a good fit and I worked with this person about ten years ago, so I'm going to hit the Apollo ‘A’. I'm going to hit 'save contact'.

Let me double check the rule right now. Large enterprise sales. Okay. Perfect. I'm going to add them directly to this sequence because I think they'd be a good fit.

So and, actually, one nice thing with the Chrome extension is that you can add notes that will carry over to your Apollo account from here. And I just want to put a note of what he last worked there. Oh, boy. K. Longer than I thought. But we did work together.

I'm going to log that there just to have some reminders for and I'm going to send that manual email, and I want to personalize it.

So for your prospecting, you're always going to want to add more contacts to your sequence and research them so that when you go to do the task, that'll be a lot easier. And you'll notice I've got tasks lined up for this sequence already. And I'm going to bang through some of those in my afternoon session and I'll show you how that'll work as well.

So, I like to do things in blocks. I'll take care of my dials, my LinkedIn, etc. I've got a number of LinkedIn connections to do here. One of the nice things about that is it’s very easy with that Chrome extension in Apollo. And I like to leave their pages up so that if there's anything interesting there, pop it into the notes.

So I'll just go with these three for now. If they posted anything interesting, anything I can use, any changes at the organization, I like to pop it in the notes. Nothing new there. Nothing new to throw in there right now. That's okay. I still like to check.

I've got a bunch of calls and emails to do. I'm going to go send one of these emails now. Again, when I'm prospecting and researching, I put those notes in there, and one of them was for this individual. So I've got an email to Sam. I left myself a note here because this was somebody that I had previously known, and their company was acquired. It was something I can use when I'm putting together this email. So I wanted to personalize this.

Okay. So that looks perfect and I'll hit 'schedule'. So that's what it's going to be like for me in my afternoons when I've got an hour set aside for handling my sequence tasks. So I'm going to make my calls, connect on LinkedIn, send my emails, and move the ball forward on all the leads I'm putting into the sequence.

Now you know how to run cold email campaigns from inside of Apollo. You'll use sequences. You'll follow-up. You'll diversify that follow-up, and you'll book lots of meetings.
`}],A=[{title:"A system that works",wistiaId:"xj2i3ktvi8",length:"2:25",description:(0,a.jsxs)("div",{className:"space-y-6",children:[(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"What is the goal of cold calls exactly? And how do the most successful sellers use them to optimize their outbound?"}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"Join James as he sets the stage for cold calling in Apollo."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"You’ll learn the fundamentals of a cold calling system that works, and why making calls remains an indispensable tool in today's sales landscape. (Sneak peek: 57% of execs say they prefer a phone call over email.)"})]}),deepLink:{heading:"Find and close your next deal in Apollo",url:"/sign-up",linkText:"Sign up for free"},transcript:`In this course, we're covering cold calls, and it's for beginners, advanced sellers, anybody that wants to make a positive impact on their business and take more control over their success, not less.

Cold calling is when we call somebody that we don't know, they don't know us. Right? It's a cold lead, but you can think of it as a lottery ticket. And it truly is.

There's so many ways cold calls can make a difference and be better than cold emails. You get immediate feedback. You might go into that first meeting with a relationship started. That meeting's going to go a lot better. But you also get access to people that will never end up reading your emails. 

If you aren't doing it, you're giving your competition an unfair advantage. Fifty seven percent of folks in the C suite or vice presidents say they prefer the phone over email. Seven out of ten buyers take calls from providers they've never worked with, and eight out of ten take calls from providers they've worked with before.

So what is the goal of a cold call? The goal of cold call… is it to prospect or sell the product right there? No. It's none of those things.

It's to move to the next step. The goal of a cold call is to sell whatever that next step is. That's usually the meeting. 

The most successful sellers use cold calls as part of their outbound lead gen strategy. They mix it in with cold emails and LinkedIn. They're following up and it's diversified, and they all help impact each other. Their cold emails work better. Their cold calls work better.

So what's the challenge? A low percentage of calls, you're actually going to connect with somebody and book a meeting, and it's going to be uncomfortable. A lot of folks want to avoid it. They'll do anything to avoid it.

Cold calling is a waste of time if you don't have a process and a system that works. That's what this course is about. Getting you set up with a system that works, and that is having highly targeted leads with phone numbers, having an effective script and a framework for your calls and your voice mails, making cold calls part of a diversified follow-up sequence, and doing dial blocks where you log everything in one place so you know what's working. You can improve your performance. You can AB test. You can get better every single month. 

At the end of this course, you're going to be ready to run cold call dial blocks right out of your Apollo account with your highest priority leads. So join me in the next video where I'm going to show you how to find great targeted leads with phone numbers, and we're going to get you set up to make dials right out of your Apollo account.

See you soon.
`},{title:"Finding leads & setting up",wistiaId:"orjy7emlbi",length:"6:28",description:(0,a.jsxs)("div",{className:"space-y-6",children:[(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"Amazing calls start with amazing leads."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"In this lesson, James teaches how to whittle down your lead list to those you should prioritize first, and how to set up your Dialer for peak performance."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"You’ll learn how to:"}),(0,a.jsx)(i.A,{color:"purple",items:["Source highly-targeted leads with verified phone numbers","Set up the Dialer for seamless calling directly from your account","Use call dispositions for streamlined tracking and automation","Maximize efficiency with voicemail drops","And more!"]})]}),deepLink:{heading:"Like what you're learning?",url:"https://app.apollo.io/#/login",linkText:"Do it in Apollo"},transcript:`In this video, we're going to cover how to set up your Apollo account to make cold calls and get leads with phone numbers.

First, we're going to go find leads with phone numbers, both new ones, and I'm going to show you how to find leads that you've already saved that have good phone numbers for cold calls as well. Then we're going to go set up the Apollo Dialer. If you're on the Pro or Custom plan, you can make your dials right from inside your Apollo account. It couldn't be easier. Then we're going to go set up something called call dispositions. It's an easy way of logging what happened on a call and automating some of that follow-up activity as well. So let's go hop into Apollo. Again, follow along and pause if you need more time.

So we're at the home page. Let's go click on 'search' because if we want to make cold calls, we got to have leads with phone numbers. So the first thing I'm going to do is go to my saved searches and load up my VIP lead saved search. If you're going to have a finite amount of time to make calls, make sure you're calling leads that you're excited about. If they pick up, you'll be thrilled. The biggest and best potential.

So this is my saved search. I'm going to go to my net new, and I'm going to save a page of these with mobile. So when you get to this screen, click on 'mobile numbers' here. Check this box, and for every lead it can find a mobile number for, it'll attach it and charge you the mobile credit.

Now I also want to mine all the leads I've already saved. So I'm going to turn off this save search and go over to my saved leads.

And there's a way to find the best leads with cold call numbers in here by going to 'more filters' and finding this one that says ‘phone status and confidence’ under miscellaneous. There's a little tack there. Pin it over to your main filters. And when you open that, you'll see, ‘does contact have a phone number?’ Yes or no? I'm looking for ones that do, ‘mobile’, ‘work’, and I think ‘corporate’. And you'll see there's a ‘phone number status’. Apollo tracks if numbers seem like they're good, if people are picking up. I'm going to prioritize just the ones where Apollo knows it's valid, and it looks like that's going to give me two hundred and thirty leads. Perfect. That's a great amount to start with. 

So here's my two hundred and thirty leads with phone numbers. Now I want to keep these organized. I actually don't have a sequence yet with cold calls in it to move them into. So I'm going to select all of these and hit 'list' right here, ‘add to list’. I'm going to create a new list, called ‘call leads’.

And that's how we could find new leads, make sure we're getting the mobile number, sorting through the ones we've already got saved. And if you want to organize them in a list, if you don't have a sequence already set up to move them into, you'll be good to go there. 

Now let's go set up our Dialer. So from the home screen, let's go to 'settings'. You'll see that button on the bottom left. And once you're in the settings screen you'll see there's a button that's called 'phone numbers' on the left navigation panel. Once you click that, if you don't have a number set up you'll see it says ‘no phone number set up’, ‘set up a phone number’. If you're on the Pro or Custom plan, you can do this and dial right from inside Apollo.

First thing you're going to have to do is choose a number. I really don't care. You can pop in an area code or country code up here and influence the ones it's showing to you, but I'm just going to choose this one in California because I'm going to tell Apollo to use a local phone number by default. It'll pick a number closest to the one I'm calling when I'm doing my dial block.

Then we've got to choose how we want to handle our outgoing or incoming calls. In both cases, you can choose to do it from the browser or bridge it over to another number. For my outgoing calls, I'm going to make them through the browser. I find that's nice and simple.

And for my incoming calls, I'm going to bridge those over to my cell phone so that if I'm not at my desk, I never miss it. 

I'm also going to choose to record all my voice calls. You could also set up voice mail drops right here on this screen. Those are prerecorded voice mails that you can just hit one button and then drop it when you call somebody and they don't pick up.

I made a morning and an afternoon one for the type of buyer I'm going to be calling here in a second. So I'm going to upload those and have them saved for when I'm doing my dial block. You just need to give it a name and hit 'save'.

I'm going to upload one more as I like to have a morning and afternoon version for all my voicemail drops.

And now I've got a morning and afternoon voice mail drop. I don't even need to say anything. I could just hit the button when I'm dialing, and I'll show you that in just a minute. 

Once you got your phone number set up and you've told Apollo how you want to handle your incoming or outgoing calls, you've recorded or uploaded some voicemail drops, let's go set up how we're going to log our calls in Apollo. That's called call dispositions.

On the left hand navigation panel, open up 'sales engagement' and click on 'Dialer'.

Once that loads, you'll see there's call dispositions and triggers.

Read through the call dispositions, and it'll make sense to you pretty quickly. This is going to be a drop down that appears when you're making your call so you can log what happened, whether it be ‘left a voicemail’, ‘busy’, ‘wrong number,’ or that you ‘connected’ with somebody. On the left hand side, you'll see the options for the drop down. On the right, you'll see what that means. ‘Not connected’, keep somebody in a sequence, ‘connected’ takes them out.

At the bottom, triggers are a way of automating changing the contact stage. So you can set what happens to that contact stage after you log a call. For example, ‘connected negative ‘will update the contact stage to ‘not interested’. 

If something's missing from the call dispositions, some sort of situation that might occur when you're making your cold calls, just hit 'add disposition' at the top right.This way you can give it the name, the option that will appear in the drop down while you're making your dials, and tell Apollo if that means they were connected, take them out of the sequence, or not connected. They should stay in. You could also log if that is a positive, a neutral, or a negative thing for that call. Once you're all done here, just scroll to the bottom and hit 'save'.

And now you're ready to make calls inside your Apollo account. In the next video, I'm going to show you how to add calls to your sequences and the secret to maximizing the number of meetings you book. See you there.
`},{title:"Adding calls to sequences",wistiaId:"ox6ui87arn",length:"6:11",description:(0,a.jsxs)("div",{className:"space-y-6",children:[(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"The top 1% of sellers create diversified sequences that include cold calls."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"Just “making the call” isn’t enough. You need a game plan. A series of touch points to warm up your leads and maintain contact."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"Luckily, Apollo makes this step incredibly easy. In this lesson, James will walk you through:"}),(0,a.jsx)(i.A,{color:"purple",items:["Adding call steps to your sequences","Cloning and customizing sequences based on phone number availability","A simple cold call framework you can follow for every call","Using dynamic variables to create personalized scripts","And more!"]})]}),deepLink:{heading:"Like what you're learning?",url:"https://app.apollo.io/#/login",linkText:"Do it in Apollo"},transcript:`In this video, we're going to cover adding cold calls to sequences and the secret to maximizing the number of meetings you book. 

Apollo makes adding cold calls to your outbound workflow really easy, and that's important because that secret to maximizing the number of meetings you book depends on it. The folks that book the least meetings are the ones that just take their leads out of Apollo and work them onesie-twosie or manually or just with, you know, emails from their inbox.

Just putting leads into sequences and keeping it organized will give you a 3x boost, but the people booking the most meetings and the best meetings, the ones you want, they're following up, and they're diversifying that follow-up. They're sending emails. They're connecting on LinkedIn, and they're making phone calls. That's where the best meetings are. That's where you want to be. 

So we're going to go into Apollo and set up our sequences so they’ve got calls in them. We're going to take an existing one and add calls, and then we're going to clone one. So we've got one for calls and one for leads where we don't have a phone number. Then we're going to move leads with phone numbers into our sequence. We're going to add scripts so that everything is nice and easy. Again, follow along in your Apollo account and pause if you need more time.

So we're at the home page. Let's go add those calls to our sequences. Let's click on 'sequences', and I'm going to go to my VIP leads first. I'm going to keep this sequence as is, but I'm going to add dials to it as well.

I'm going to try to call all the leads that go in here. So let's add a step and select 'phone call'. It's going to pop in at the bottom. That's okay. I'm going to show you how to move it around. So I want this to happen one day after I do that first email. So I'm going to select ‘one day’, make it a high priority. So we'll hit 'continue' and pop it in.

Let's add one more phone call step to occur after that second email. I'm going to have that happen one day after as well. High priority and mark 'continue'.

Any steps you add to a sequence, they're going to pop in at the bottom, but you can drag and drop them. So on this one, I'm going to move it to be right after my first email.

You'll notice that that happens one day after that email. I just need to put my script in there and I'll be good to go. I'm also going to move this call to occur after my second email.

And that's looking good. I also have another sequence for the leads that come in from marketing. Sometimes those have phone numbers, sometimes they don't. So I'm going to make two versions of this. One for the leads that have a phone number and one for those that don't.

So let's click on the three dots and hit 'clone', and I'm going to rename this one ‘leads from marketing cold call’ and hit 'clone'.

And just like that other one, I'm going to add the cold call steps to occur when I think they'll be best. I always do at least two cold calls. Give yourself a chance to leave some voicemails, and maybe you get lucky and they pick up. I just need to add the cold calls like I did on the other one, and this one's going to be good to go.

You'll notice when we put those call steps into our sequences, there's a notes field and it allows you to use dynamic variables. This is so you could pop in a script for your call or your voicemail and and actually have Apollo put the lead details right there in the script to make it super easy when you're making your dials. 

Now if you're new to cold calling, you're nervous, or you need a refresher, there's frameworks and scripts in the resource kit. And a simple framework for thinking about cold calls is this.

The first thing you're going to want to say is who you are and where you're calling from. Again, we're catching them off guard. They weren't expecting our call. They don't know who we are. Let's tell them that. 

The next thing we're going to do is include a point of connection, something to warm them up or build rapport. So when you do your pre call research, you're looking to see if you have mutual connections. You're in the same group on LinkedIn. You both went to an event. Anything that will familiarize you to them and humanize you. 

Then you're going to have to let them know why you're even calling in the first place. So a note on the pain you can solve, a valuable piece of information. Give them a reason to stay on the phone with you. Maybe you bring up other companies that are very similar to theirs that you've been able to help in a big way. 

And last, you're going to want to ask for the meeting or whatever your call to action is there. Even if they say no, it's still a great chance to ask a question or two. You can always get some piece of information that'll improve your ability to sell them in the future.

So I'm going to go pop in and add my scripts to my dial steps. Just go to your sequence, click on the phone call step, the three dots where you can select 'edit'. Now put in your call script, voicemail script, whatever makes sense for you. I actually prioritize the voicemail script because there's no back and forth there. That's one I should be able to get perfect and the script is really useful. So I'll continue, and I'm copying this from the resource kit. Do the same and personalize it to your situation and pop them into your call steps. 

So now we just need to add leads. So there's a couple ways you can do that. You can go to your matching saved search for your sequence. I have a VIP sequence. I have a VIP lead save search. I'll go to net new, and I'll pull some new leads and pop them right in there. I'll select these first three. And instead of just saving, I'm going to save them and add them to this sequence, and I'm going to pull those mobile numbers by clicking right here as well.

We also saved some of our leads with phone numbers directly into a list. I've got a VIP list, so I can select the ones I want to add from here and put directly into the sequence.

And now we've got our sequences with dials in them, contacts in them, and our scripts. 

In the next video, I'm going to show you how to run your dial blocks right out of Apollo. We're going to tie it all together, and you'll be able to watch me do it as well. I'm going to make some cold calls, and I'm going to show you how you can make sure you're improving every week, logging your calls and analyzing your performance. See you in the next video.
`},{title:"Making the call",wistiaId:"7hlw63lunq",length:"10:00",description:(0,a.jsxs)("div",{className:"space-y-6",children:[(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"Watch James in action as he puts it all together and demonstrates how to do effective cold calls from Apollo."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"This is where the rubber meets the road. In this lesson, you’ll observe James:"}),(0,a.jsx)(i.A,{color:"purple",items:["Prep like a pro by researching leads on LinkedIn","Use the Dialer to cold call actual humans (!!) ","Leave voicemails with just a click","Log and transcribe calls for better record-keeping and follow-up","Review call metrics to find areas for improvement","And more!"]})]}),deepLink:{heading:"Like what you're learning?",url:"https://app.apollo.io/#/login",linkText:"Do it in Apollo"},transcript:`In this video, I'm going to make some cold calls in Apollo and show you how to tie it all together. I'm going to show you how to use your Apollo account so you can do great cold calls and book meetings with your ideal prospects. 

The first thing we're going to do is our pre call research. It's really important so you could have something to say to build rapport or warmth with your prospect and then also to tie the value prop back to their business. 

I'm going to make some calls in Apollo so you'll know how to use the Apollo Dialer. 

We're going to use voicemail drops so we can very quickly drop a great voicemail that we know is going to sound good and transcribe well. 

I'll show you how to log your calls and even how to transcribe them and attach it to your leads. 

Now before we go do any of that, let's remove blockers. Any reason we might not do our cold calls, a great way to do that is to block time on your calendar. Put it in there. Color code it. Make sure it’s at times that are going to be ideal for you to be doing your cold calls. And ideally, it's times when people are more likely to pick up.

I'm going to hop into Apollo and do some of this research, make some calls, follow along in your Apollo account, pause if you need more time.

So we're at the home screen. I gotta make some cold calls, but I need to research one of my new leads before I can call them. It'll be the first call today. I like to do my dial blocks out of the 'tasks' screen. You'll notice it right on the sidebar. And when you get there, you can choose what type of activity you want to do and only see that, whether it be calls or emails or adding people on LinkedIn. 

So I'm going to go to calls, and I've already got some set up from my call tasks and my sequences, and I've gotta research a couple of these. I'm going to start with this one right here. 

Now you could dial right off that screen real quickly. I like to click in all the way just to see what notes I've got. You'll see on the right side of the screen, there's your activities. That's everything you've done with that lead, but you can also pin notes to the top. So I'm going to go to LinkedIn and see if there's anything I can pull off their account, save it to the notes, and have it available for when I'm doing my calls.

First thing I like to do is just see if there's shared connections. There is. I'm going to save this into my notes under activities. Mutual connections.

I noticed that we're both alumni of the same university, and I don't always use it, but when I'm a customer of a prospect's company, I like to at least note it down.

Now once you've got your notes, anything you think might come in handy when you're dialing, you can click 'pin note to top' and log that note, and that'll be available to you on the record when you're making your dials. I'll refresh this, and there's my notes from LinkedIn. 

You don't need to spend that long researching, and sometimes I like to research a little bit every time I'm calling. Most of the time, I don't get somebody, but I could start to accrue more and more useful stuff.

Let's go make some dials, though, because most of these, I've already researched once or twice.

I'm going to work my way down the dial list here starting with this one. I've got some good notes. Time to call.

Blaze: Hello?

James: Hi. Is this Blaze Vidi?

Blaze: Hey, dude. I'm in the middle of this email. I was going to reply back to you.

James: Oh, no. You know, if you're in the middle of something, I appreciate you being, polite about it. Is there a better time to talk? This is James O'Sullivan. I'm sure you knew that from all my emails and calls. Is there a better time to call, in a little bit?

Blaze: I can if you can give me a call on Friday, that'd be good?

James: What what time is the best time? I'll throw it on our calendar, a little five minute calendar invite. And that email is going to go great. I promise you.

Blaze: How about how about ten thirty?

James: You're central. Right?

Blaze: Yeah.

James: Okay. Perfect. Well, you're going to end your week strong. You're going to be excited about that call. So hope the email goes well. Have a great rest of your day. I'll talk to you soon. Okay?

Blaze: Sounds good.

James: Okay. Thanks, bud.

Time to log that call. I try to have some fun with folks, especially when they're that polite about being annoyed about the call prospecting.

And I'm not going to put ‘connected’ yet because it really pushed me off here. So I'm going to say ‘keep and dial block’. That's a disposition I added, and we'll log that call.

You'll notice that it just pops to the next dial in your list when you're on your calls. So I'm going to call this one. I'd already previously researched this when I got a voicemail.

Scott: Hello?

James: Hi. Is this Scott Knabe?

Scott: Yes.

James: Hey, Scott. This is James O'Sullivan. I've been, emailing you quite a bit lately. How are you doing?

Scott: I'm doing great. How are you?

James: I'm doing great. Do you have two seconds to chat? I know this is a cold call, but do you have thirty seconds just so I could run through why I'm so excited to chat with you?

Scott: I do. I did have a question for you, though. I was wondering why your phone number came up as spam risk.

James: Probably because of how many times I've called you in the last week. I promise you, I don't get paid to stalk. If you just give me thirty seconds, I'll run you through it. And if it's not for you, I won't ever call you again, at least for a month. Is that okay?

Scott: Sounds good. 

James: I did my research, and congrats on all the success at Loan Payment Pro. I know you guys have been growing really big. I've worked with a lot of other companies just like yours at the same stage of growth, and the economics of the entry-level salespeople is upside down right now. And I've heard that it's very difficult getting the right type of people to sell for what you're doing. Does that align with what you're seeing?

Scott:  It does. It does. I'd say that's a fair statement.

James: Okay. So, yeah, like I said, I was very excited to chat with you because we work with companies just like yours. We've been able to help them boost the performance, not only of the upside down entry-level reps, but also with their veterans that are hard to manage up because most of the revenue is coming from them. We're seeing around thirty, forty percent boost, and that's only after one quarter. So, we work with Lindy.ai, Foco, Contoso. Can I just get on your calendar for a quick meeting so I could walk you through this, earn some of your trust, show you that we're credible on this sort of thing, and just see if it might potentially be a good fit for what you're doing over there?

Scott:  Absolutely. That I don't see any problem with that at all.

James: What days look good for you this week?

Scott:  You know what? Like, Thursday and Friday would be ideal.

James: How about this? What time works for you on Thursday? I think you'll be so excited. We'll do a fast follow-up on Friday. What times are good for you Thursday?

Scott:  How about two o'clock central time? Time?

James:  Okay. Perfect. Well, I'm really looking forward to it. I'll send you a calendar invite with some details of what I was hoping to chat about, but have a great rest of your day. Looking forward to Thursday. Thank you, Scott.

Scott:  Alright. You too, my man. Take care. Bye.

Time to log that one. I got a little bit flustered, but I'm excited about that opportunity. ‘Connected positive’, and I'll send that calendar invite after I do one more dial:

Your call has been forwarded to voicemail. The person you're trying to reach is not available. At the tone, please record your message. When you have finished recording, you may hang up.

I’m going to use the voicemail drop.

But I want to go back and transcribe that call I had with Scott because he was a lot more engaging than I was anticipating, and he mentioned some things in that call that I want to make sure I've got saved. 

To transcribe any call, just click on 'calls' on your navigation sidebar, find the call you're looking for, and hit 'start transcription'. And there we go. The transcription is up. It'll break down how much you're talking, the prospect, everything that was said with time stamps, wonderful details to have attached to your record. 

Now the last thing I'm going to show you is how you could track your calls and the metrics and what's happening from it.

Just go to 'analytics' on your sidebar, and you'll notice that there's a created by Apollo report called 'call engagement performance'. If you click on that, it's going to break down all your call data, which allows you to start understanding not only how many dials you make, but how many connections you're getting, how many are ending positive. This will allow you to benchmark yourself day after day, week after week, make sure you're headed in the right direction. 

Now you know how to make cold calls in Apollo and how to set yourself up for great cold call dial blocks.

That's important because the best sellers are mixing dials into their outbound sequences. Email, calls, LinkedIn, and anything else you can think of that will help influence your prospects to meet with you and then eventually do business with you. So good luck, and happy selling.
`}],v=[{title:"Why LinkedIn?",wistiaId:"pvplvcea1c",length:"2:38",description:(0,a.jsxs)("div",{className:"space-y-6",children:[(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"LinkedIn is the world’s largest professional network, with over 140 million people logging in every day."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"In this first lesson, discover why LinkedIn is such a goldmine for prospecting and how pairing it with Apollo can supercharge your pipeline."})]}),deepLink:{heading:"Find and close your next deal in Apollo",url:"/sign-up",linkText:"Sign up for free"},transcript:`In this course, we're going to cover how to use LinkedIn and Apollo to prospect.

LinkedIn is a really powerful sales resource. It is by far the most popular professional social network. It's got nearly a billion users and a lot of them use it a lot. Sixteen percent of users log in every day and forty-eight percent of those users log in every month.

People use LinkedIn to manage their past and present professional contacts or to network, recruit, look for a job, learn job-related skills, build their personal brand, or join groups to know what's being talked about in their profession or industry. 

With all this activity on LinkedIn, it makes it really easy to build rapport or find points of connection with your prospects. There are a lot of ways to learn details about your prospects that you can use to personalize your outbound messaging. Their posts and comments, the career highlights they have on their page, mutual connections and the groups they're in, even their interests, people they follow, companies, newsletters, groups, schools.

And this is why the sellers that research their prospects say LinkedIn is the best resource to do so. And eighty-seven percent of sellers say that social selling has been a positive for their business.

So what does it look like when you’ve got LinkedIn and Apollo? Well, now when you find a great lead on LinkedIn, you could save it back to Apollo. You can enrich it, get all that contact information, including the mobile number. And you could interact with these prospects not just on one platform but across everything — LinkedIn, email, and phone. 

And that's really important because the best sellers, the people with the highest meeting booked rates, they're diversifying their follow-up. They're following up four or five times and they're doing it across email, phone, and LinkedIn. And that's what you want to be doing. 

So you might have some questions like, how do I find the right people on LinkedIn? And what do I do when I’ve found them? What's appropriate? What's a good way to interact with folks taking it off LinkedIn with email or phone? 

And that's what we're going to cover in this course. How to find the right people on LinkedIn, how to save them back to your Apollo, get all the contact information, and then taking those interactions on and off LinkedIn.

At the end of this course, you're going to know how to find great leads, leads good for your business, and how to generate meetings with them. So join me in the next video where I'm going to walk you through creative searches to find great leads and how to save them to Apollo and get all that contact information, including the mobile number.
`},{title:"Finding & saving new leads",wistiaId:"dzhjsgrqdc",length:"6:50",description:(0,a.jsxs)("div",{className:"space-y-6",children:[(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"Not sure how to pinpoint the right leads on LinkedIn?"}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"In this lesson, James spills the beans on how to find best-fit leads on LinkedIn and easily save their contact info to Apollo using the Chrome extension."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"You’ll learn how to:"}),(0,a.jsx)(i.A,{color:"purple",items:["Get more creative in your searches to find your perfect leads","Use the Chrome extension to attach notes & save contact info","Add contacts to lists and sequences without ever leaving LinkedIn","Bulk save contacts from company pages","And more!"]})]}),deepLink:{heading:"Ready to give Apollo’s Chrome extension a go?",linkText:"Download it free",url:"https://chromewebstore.google.com/detail/apolloio-free-b2b-phone-n/alhgpfoeiimagjlnfekdhkjlkiomcapa"},transcript:`In this video, I'm going to show you how to find the right people on LinkedIn and then save them so you can get all of their contact information.

We're going to do that by covering four things. 

The first one is creative searches on LinkedIn. How to find great leads that are targeted or have some built-in point of connection or something you can use to build rapport or warmth when you're reaching out. 

The second thing I'm going to cover is how to save those leads back to Apollo using the Apollo Chrome extension. That way, you've got all their contact information. 

The third thing I'm going to show you is how to save leads while you're on LinkedIn directly into your list and sequences. 

And then I'll show you how to bulk save contacts directly from company pages or just narrow it down to the ones you don't currently have saved as leads. 

Before we do any of that though, we need to get the Apollo Chrome extension. There's a link in the resource kit. Let's go download that and get it installed right now. There's no reason not to. It's free to use, got great ratings, and it could do a heck of a lot to help you with your prospecting and your selling. I've got mine installed, of course, so I'm going to hop into LinkedIn and start searching for some leads. Feel free to follow along in your LinkedIn and pause if you need more time. 

I'm logged into LinkedIn. I'm ready to find some great leads. You'll notice I've got my Apollo Chrome extension installed and enabled. It should show up on the side of your screen. It'll have the Apollo ‘A’ on it. Let's just go find some quick leads so I can show you how to save things. 

I'm just going to search for ‘sales leader’ and use that as a job title keyword for people. I'll take the first one I see here and you'll see that on any profile that you go to when you hit that Apollo ‘A’ button, you'll see their detail card from Apollo. In this case, I don't have it as a contact saved. I'm not connected with this person on LinkedIn, and I could just hit 'save contact'. That'll save it back in Apollo. I now have access to whatever contact information was in Apollo. And if I'd like to access the mobile number, I'll just click right here on 'access mobile number'.

A lot of times you can find great leads just by searching for ‘job title’ persona, and selecting the 'people' category.

I'm going to get a little bit more creative here because I like to find leads where there's something built into how I found it that gives me something to use when I go outbound. They said something in a comment or they were talking about a topic I'm an expert in. 

So I'm going to put in a keyword at the top and just see if anybody's talking about this. Sometimes I'll find a post from somebody, and it's, like, perfect for what I'm selling, but usually, I have to check the comments.

I'm going to check this one because it looks to tie in with the type of thing I sell at Apollo Academy. This person wouldn't be a great lead, but their post has forty-three comments. So I'm going to check in there. I usually just check what people are saying, see if there's something interesting where I can sincerely bring it up and say, hey. I liked your post. And I'm also checking the titles.

So this looks like it'll be a good lead. It's the right title. They actually work for a company not far from me. It's the right type of company. I'm going to save this as a lead using the Apollo Chrome extension.

Now I've got all the contact information.

I'm also going to add a note. So you can add a note directly to the contact, the lead in Apollo, by going to 'activities' and putting it in here. I like to log it to the top so I don't miss it later when I'm going to reach out.

And now I've got a new lead there as well. Another way to get creative is to use ‘job title’ in some of the additional filters that LinkedIn has. So I'm going to put ‘sales VP’, go to 'people', and then I'm going to choose ‘second level connections’. I don't want to see people I'm already connected with. I'm going to import all of them into Apollo anyways in the next video. I'm going to choose ‘second’. That means we have a mutual contact on LinkedIn. And then I'm going to hit 'all filters', and I'm going to add something else.

You'll notice that you can use ‘location’, ‘current’ and ‘past company’ (if you want to look for folks that worked at a company you've been at before), ‘school’, ‘industry’, and people that they follow.

So I'm going to try to get a little bit indulgent here. I'm going to look for people that meet my persona that are in the Chicago area, and I also want them to be followers of Jill Konrath. She's put out some amazing sales books. “SNAP Selling” is one of my favorites. Anybody that follows Jill Konrath will like what I sell as part of Apollo Academy, and I'll hit 'show results'.

So this search is great. I've got three hundred results with multiple potential points of connection or things I can use to build warmth.

As opposed to working these one at a time, I'm going to use the Apollo Chrome extension to select all on a couple pages and add them directly into a sequence. So I'm going to hit 'add a sequence'. You can do 'list' as well. 'Chicago VIP leads from LinkedIn' and 'add now'. That way I can build a sequence around not only LinkedIn tasks that I'll be adding, but also email and phone, and I could include some notes in there about these potential points of connection.

There are lots of creative ways to find leads on LinkedIn. I love to check the comments on influencers in my industry or even comments on my competitors' posts. You could also sign up for groups that would attract the type of person you're wishing to sell to. We've got a list of these and others in the resource kit. So download the resource kit and check out those examples to see what might work for you.

The last thing I want to show you is how you can use the Apollo Chrome extension when you're on a company page. You'll notice that I went to a company page here, and it's giving me a bunch of details about that organization. But when you click on the 'people' tab, it'll actually give you the option of bulk saving contacts from that company or only saving the ones that are net new. So if you're working targeted accounts, if you've been tasked with getting into a specific organization, this is a great way to very quickly add new contacts that you don't already have in your Apollo account. 

So now you're ready to find leads on LinkedIn and save them to Apollo. But join me in the next video where I'm going to show you how to import all your existing LinkedIn connections into Apollo, enrich them, get all the contact information, and how to leverage those four LinkedIn tasks available in sequences.
`},{title:"Importing connections  & using sequences",wistiaId:"cfz11p3bqd",length:"7:13",description:(0,a.jsxs)("div",{className:"space-y-6",children:[(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"Finding new leads is great. But what about the LinkedIn connections you already have?"}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"In this lesson, learn how to turn luke-warm connections into hot leads by importing them into Apollo and maximizing their potential with sequences."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"You’ll learn how to:"}),(0,a.jsx)(i.A,{color:"purple",items:["Import LinkedIn connections into Apollo via a CSV","Enrich leads to get accurate contact info","Organize LinkedIn leads into lists and sequences","Use Apollo’s 4 LinkedIn tasks to boost your follow-up game","And more!"]})]}),deepLink:{heading:"Like what you're learning?",url:"https://app.apollo.io",linkText:"Do it in Apollo"},transcript:`In this video, I'm going to show you how to import all your LinkedIn connections into Apollo and save them as leads and how to leverage sequences both for your new leads you're saving off LinkedIn as well as your imported connections.

And that's a big deal because you want to work all your leads, not some, not just the new ones or not just the active connections. You want to work all the leads you have access to, and you don't want to limit yourself to just interacting with folks on LinkedIn. You want to work your leads, especially your best ones, across LinkedIn, phone, and email. The best sellers diversify their outbound follow-up, and they're not reaching out just once or twice. They're reaching out four or five times across LinkedIn, email, and phone.

That's what this video is all about. I'm going to show you how to bring those active connections you've got on LinkedIn and bring them into Apollo so that you can enrich them and get the contact information, including the mobile number. Then I'm going to cover those four LinkedIn tasks you can use in sequences so that you can work your leads effectively across LinkedIn, the phone, and emails. Why don't you follow along with me and pause if you need more time? 

It's really great being able to bulk upload contacts into Apollo, and we're going to do that with our LinkedIn connections now. There's a lot of different ways you can use those leads. To find where you do that and also get help, click on 'search'. And then at the top of where your search results would be, you'll see a little button that says 'import', and it's a drop down. Select that and 'bulk import from CSV'. This is the button we're going to hit when we have our LinkedIn file, but you'll notice that there's a sample template to make sure whatever you're uploading is matching what Apollo's going to be looking for, and there's an FAQ at the bottom to answer any questions you might have about how to do this. 

Since we want to upload our LinkedIn connections, let's pop over to LinkedIn. I'll show you where to download it from.

So hop into LinkedIn. Go to your face that's at the top and click on it. You'll see an option for a settings and privacy menu. Click in there, and then go to ‘data privacy’. You'll notice that there's an option to get a copy of your data. Let's select that. And I've got mine available to download now. I've got a lot of connections. It took a little bit of time. Depending on how many connections you have, it might be instant or it might be a couple of hours. To request it, all you have to do is select 'want something in particular' and ask for ‘connections’. Once you've done that, you'll be able to download it to your computer.

You'll need to hop into that file and delete the top couple lines because Apollo is just looking for the titles of each column and then the data.

Once you've got your connections from LinkedIn in a CSV file, let's go upload it.

Once it's uploaded, it's going to look at the column titles and try to match it up with fields in Apollo. So it's got first and last name okay… this one will be LinkedIn URL, contact email, account name… position would be contact title, and I don't care to sync the date I was connected into Apollo.

If you want it to be assigned to yourself or somebody else or to override details you already have in Apollo, you can set that right at the bottom and then select 'import'.

To access your LinkedIn connections that you just uploaded as a CSV file, click on 'search' and then open 'more filters'.

You'll see under ‘created source’, there's a filter called 'contact CSV import'. Open that, and you'll see all your uploads of contacts into Apollo. The one I just uploaded is right here, ‘LinkedIn connections export’. I'll select that and hit 'apply filters'.

And then let's go to the button that says 'enrich', and select 'enrich emails'.

If you'd like to get the mobile number as well, you can select all your leads or specific ones that might be more important or ones that you're going to put into different lists or sequences. So I'll select one right here and hit 'enrich’, ‘mobile number’.

And now I've got the mobile and the email for that connection from LinkedIn.

A good way to organize your LinkedIn connections is by putting them into a list, something that labels them as active LinkedIn connections. That way you could take advantage of all the LinkedIn tasks available in Apollo sequences. So I'm going to select all of these contacts, and I'm going to add them to a list, ‘LinkedIn active connections’.

Now I'll be able to just pop into my saved list and have all my active LinkedIn connections in one folder, ready to be filtered further into different sequences potentially or one sequence that will have all my LinkedIn tasks available.

So let's pop into our sequences, and I'll show you those four tasks you can use when you're working with your active or new leads from LinkedIn. 

You'll notice I've got a new sequence called ‘LinkedIn connections’ here, and it has no steps in it. So I'm going to hit 'add a step', and here you'll find that there are four LinkedIn tasks available when you're building your sequence. They're all easy to do, whether you're in Apollo or you're on LinkedIn using the Apollo Chrome extension.

The first one's really popular. Everybody uses 'send connection request'. You generally want to be connected to folks you're trying to sell. 

But the second one, 'send message', is underutilized. Everybody's sending cold emails, but potentially, it's going to be better if you send somebody a message on LinkedIn. And this one is only for people you're actively connected to. It's not using an InMail credit. It's just a normal message. When you know you're connected with somebody, this is a great way to diversify your follow-up. And, potentially, they'll see it there if they didn't see the email or you're getting blocked by spam. 

The other two steps will allow you to warm people up, especially if you're working targeted leads or you're willing to chase after an opportunity for months. 

'View profile' is a way just to show up on that little button that the prospect might see when LinkedIn says there's been people checking out your profile. They might see your name there and click through because they don't recognize it. 

'Interact with post' is an easy way to get noticed. Liking people's posts, commenting on them, this will remind you to go to this person's page and like or comment or interact with something they've been putting on LinkedIn.

Now I've got multiple sequences, and a few of them already had LinkedIn steps. ‘Chicago VIP leads’ is a sequence I have for saving great leads in my area from LinkedIn to start the process of working with them. When I click on 'tasks', you'll be able to sort the type of activity you've got ready to do from across all your sequences. You'll notice that I've got fifteen LinkedIn tasks already waiting to go. 

So I'm going to do these in the next video where I'm going to do some creative searches to find some new leads and reach out, taking those interactions off LinkedIn, but I'm also going to execute these LinkedIn tasks using the Apollo Chrome extension right while I'm on LinkedIn.
`},{title:"Putting it all together",wistiaId:"eiui45ip2f",length:"11:12",description:(0,a.jsxs)("div",{className:"space-y-6",children:[(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"Join James in a “day in the life” as he expertly leverages LinkedIn and Apollo to streamline his prospecting activities."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"Watch James as he:"}),(0,a.jsx)(i.A,{color:"purple",items:["Unearths high-quality leads using creative searches and LinkedIn filters","Writes and schedules an email using the Apollo Chrome extension","Instantly requests a phone number & makes a call straight from LinkedIn","Creates and executes on LinkedIn-related tasks using the extension","And more!"]})]}),deepLink:{heading:"Ready to give Apollo’s Chrome extension a go?",linkText:"Download it free",url:"https://chromewebstore.google.com/detail/apolloio-free-b2b-phone-n/alhgpfoeiimagjlnfekdhkjlkiomcapa"},transcript:`In this video, I'm going to show you how to tie it all together and take those interactions off of LinkedIn with your new leads.

I'm going to hop into my Apollo and LinkedIn accounts, and I'm going to walk you through from beginning to end. I'm going to do creative searches to find good leads for me, and I'm going to save them to Apollo so I get all their contact information. I'm going to take that interaction off LinkedIn. I'm going to personalize it using information I found while searching for those leads. I want to build rapport or warmth and connect it all together. 

I'm going to go hop into my Apollo and LinkedIn accounts and start my search. And if you want to do this as well, just pause if you need more time. 

I'm on LinkedIn. I'm going to tie it all together by doing it. I'm going to search for new leads myself, work these leads, and as opposed to just giving you examples, I'm actually going to pull through on it and do the messaging and calls as well.

So I want to find some new leads first. I'm going to do a creative search.

One of my favorite ways to do that is searching for ‘announce new role’. I just pop it into the search box, select 'posts', sort by latest, so I see the most recent.

Now this wouldn't be super useful because you're just seeing anybody that's announcing they've got a new role. But if you click on 'all filters' and scroll all the way down, there's author keywords, and there's only one box. It's for their job title.

So I put ‘VP of sales’ in there, and you'll get everybody that's got VP sales (or whatever you put in there) in their title announcing that they started a new role. And for me, I found that that's a pretty good situation to be in. Oftentimes, about two, three, four months in, they're starting to realize where they're lacking or where they're being overwhelmed. So the first one here, I'm going to click on.

And this looks like it could be a good lead. I don't know the company she works for, and it also looks like I got slightly bad timing. She was just in Chicago this week. I missed her there, but it looks like a pretty good lead. I'm going to save this one.

I'd like to do a little bit of research before I reach out. I know that she was just speaking at this event in Chicago. I don't know this company very well. I'd like to have a sense of how big the team is at the very least. Sometimes I'll do that on LinkedIn. Other times, I'll just use the Apollo Chrome extension. Sometimes it's a little bit more useful there. You'll notice they have an insights tab where you can see ‘news’, ‘technologies’, ‘hiring’, ‘funding’ news about the organization.

There's also a ‘colleagues’ tab. You can use many of the filters available to you in Apollo search, such as departments and job function. I'm going to select 'sales' and apply that.

And as it's updating, looks like there's sixteen people. So this will be perfect. I'm just going to reach out right now by hitting the 'email' button, and I've actually done this before. I've got a partial template already built, so I'm going to pull that up. 

This template was built for this search I just did, ‘announcing new role’. I just need to tie it into what I saw that they posted. 

So that works pretty good. I'm going to schedule it to go in the morning, and we're good to go. 

So I also like to use the Apollo Chrome extension to help me organize following up with people who post on my content. I'm going to go check the folks that left comments on my most recent post and try to use those to build relationships and create any opportunities that I can.

So my most recent post was this one, and I saw there's a number of comments. And sometimes people try to be funny. That just makes it really easy to have something to talk about.

This gentleman said, “This guy is too smooth. Must be AI.” If you've been watching my courses on here, you know that's not necessarily the case. 

But I'm going to follow-up with this one. So I'm going to click to request the mobile number in the Apollo Chrome extension for this lead because there was no phone number associated with the contact yet.

And I'm just going to call right now because sometimes it's better just to call when you're excited than to put it off and forget what you wanted to say or all of a sudden you find yourself nervous to make that call. They're probably not going to pick up, but I'll probably just tie it back to whatever they commented on my post and improve the odds that when I send an email, they're going to read it. But maybe we'll get lucky. 

Hi. You reached Tanner. Sorry. I can't come over the phone. Leave me a message, and I'll give you a callback as soon as I can. Thanks.

“Hey, Tanner. This is James O'Sullivan. I thought your post was funny or your comment on my post, I should say, about me being too smooth. I must be AI. This voicemail will disprove the too smooth thing. I'm definitely human. But after I checked out your profile, I was really excited about chatting with you. I'm going to shoot you an email. I'll do it in the morning. I know it's late in the day. But I'll shoot you an email tomorrow morning about what I was excited to chat with you about. Hope you're having a great day. Thanks again for the comment. Talk to you soon. Bye.”

And then I'm just going to leave a note.

So I like to leave notes on what I've said, what I've done. It doesn't need to be a lot. Just something that gives me quick clarity on what I was excited about, what I might have referenced in a voicemail. That way, there's no confusion moving forward. I just notice I'm more likely to do more activity and quicker if I know what I've done in the past. 

You can actually create tasks and to dos. On this one, I said I was going to email you in the morning. I left that voicemail today hoping that this individual will hear it shortly before that email is supposed to come through. So I'm going to go to 'tasks' on the Apollo Chrome extension and hit 'create a task'. You can select any contact that you want to associate with it, and that'll be a manual email, and I want that done tomorrow at eight thirty AM. Perfect. 

I like to spend a little bit of time each day doing creative searches or following up with people who comment on my post. I find that the quality is higher. The conversion to conversation is really high. But I still have to give myself a little bit of volume. Even if it's not much, ten or twenty prospects in one sequence with some common characteristics can really help. 

So I'm going to search for ‘chief sales officer’ this time, and I'm going to look for characteristics a little bit different from video two. So 'people', 'Chicago'. I'm going to open up 'all filters' so I can add more to this than just people that are near me with that title. And I'm going to try to find folks that went to the same university as me.

There's an event coming up at that university. It might give me something to talk about. So I'm down to 605. I'm going to choose 'second'.

So this is more than I thought it would be. These look like really good leads. I'd like to save some of these. I'll start with this one. This looks great, and I'm going to add this to my sequence for Chicago area VIP leads.

Check out the next one. This one looks really good too. A lot of mutual contacts. Going to save that one. I'm going to add it to that sequence as well. 

So this is a nice way to very quickly find lots of leads, save them, get their contact information, and then throw them into a sequence, something that you know works, it's been tested. It keeps everything organized.

This one looks even better, and we're both members of a group, the same group. So this one's good. 

And you'll notice you can very quickly find a lot of targeted leads and put them into a sequence using this method.

And the nice thing about it is that your sequences that have LinkedIn steps can be worked directly from the Apollo Chrome extension while you're on LinkedIn.

You'll notice that there's a 'task' button right from the Apollo Chrome extension. That'll pull up all the existing LinkedIn tasks you have across all your sequences. 

So the folks I just saved to that sequence are now queuing up, and they'll show up right here.

I'm not hitting ‘connect’ on any of these because I'm just making ‘connect’  the first step in the sequence. I could go through those all real quickly just by hitting 'execute task' directly from the Apollo Chrome extension. When you do that, it goes to the person's page, sends the connection request, and then it'll even use your templated connection request message with those dynamic variables. So you just got to type it up once and then Apollo will personalize it for you.

First one's done. Go to the next one and hit 'execute task'. Couldn't be simpler.

And I'll do one more, and I think I'll call it a day.

You'll notice that as I'm executing these tasks, which are 'send connection request', Apollo's keeping a log here of all the ones that are sent and if it went through or if it didn't. In this case, I've just done four very quickly, and they've all gone through along with my personalized message. 

So that's how you tie it all together. Using Apollo and LinkedIn, you can go for those individual great targeted leads where you're so excited to talk to them. You hit dial or send the email directly from the Chrome extension after you get the contact information. Or you use searches where you find folks that you could bundle together by persona or industry or common characteristics and put them into your list and sequences, and the Apollo Chrome extension will make it really easy to execute all those tasks you have on LinkedIn.

Okay that wraps up this course on how to use Apollo and LinkedIn to prospect. I hope you were able to get some great tips and tactics so you can find new leads and book lots of meetings. Happy selling.
`}],I=[{title:"Why Apollo Meetings?",wistiaId:"g7mfy775zm",length:"2:31",description:(0,a.jsxs)("div",{className:"space-y-6",children:[(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{variant:"h5",children:"If you’re still sending “Is there a time that works for everybody?” emails… there’s a better way."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"In this lesson, you’ll get introduced to the benefits of using Apollo Meetings, such as cutting down on back-and-forth emails and consolidating your tech stack."}),(0,a.jsxs)(s.A,{children:["You’ll also get a sneak peek of how this course will guide you in mastering Meetings for smoother, more efficient scheduling."," "]})]}),deepLink:{heading:"Find and close your next deal in Apollo",url:"/sign-up",linkText:"Sign up for free"},transcript:`In this course, we're going to walk through how to set up and use Apollo Meetings. Meetings empowers your prospects to schedule with you and get on your calendar in seconds. Instead of the back-and-forth emails trying to find a time that works for everyone, your prospects will simply click a link, pick a time that suits them, and be done with it.
    
Getting meetings set up brings a host of improvements. It streamlines scheduling for all your meeting types, whether they’re with you or rotating through other team members. It encourages proactive engagement for new or repeat customers, making it easy for them to get on your calendar and move business forward. It reduces the risk of no-shows with automated reminders and an easy reschedule link in the original invite and reminder emails. Additionally, it allows you to consolidate tools. Remember, Apollo is an all-in-one sales platform, and Meetings is built right in. You don’t need to search for a third-party tool—it’s already there, easy to set up, and can save you money. Furthermore, it allows you to automate meeting activities. Since it's integrated, you can tie it together with other parts of Apollo, such as automating workflows. Maybe you want to create a deal every time a new meeting is booked. You can set that up using Apollo Meetings. 

It might seem like a small thing here, but it actually drives a really big impact. It's going to help you drive more revenue and free up time for both you and your prospects, giving them a much better experience.

All of this works by integrating your calendar with Apollo and then creating custom meeting links. That’s what we’ll cover in this course. 

First, we'll set you up with Meetings. We'll connect your calendar and set a default meeting location, whether it’s Zoom, Google Meet, Microsoft Teams, or another platform. Then we’ll cover creating your custom meeting links—whether it should be a single, multi, or round-robin host situation, what days and times are available, and where the meeting should take place.

In the final video, we'll tie it all together. I’ll show you how to use your new Apollo Meetings links both within and outside of Apollo to save time, book more meetings, and make everything simpler for your prospects. Join me in the next video, where I'll walk you through getting everything set up. You’ll be up and running with Apollo Meetings in just a few minutes.
`},{title:"Getting meeting-ready",wistiaId:"77v9ehq4ul",length:"4:18",description:(0,a.jsxs)("div",{className:"space-y-6",children:[(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{variant:"h5",children:"In this lesson, James will walk you through the initial setup for Meetings."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"You’ll learn how to:"}),(0,a.jsx)(i.A,{color:"purple",items:["Connect your calendar to manage availability","Connect your meeting locations—such as Zoom, Teams, or Google Meet","Define your preferences","Install the Chrome extension so you can use meeting links in your inbox"]})]}),deepLink:{heading:"Like what you’re learning?",linkText:"Do it in Apollo",url:"https://app.apollo.io"},transcript:`In this video, we're going to walk through the initial setup for Meetings. The first thing we're going to do is connect your calendar to Apollo so that we can manage your availability when you send out your meeting links. We'll then get you connected to your meeting locations, whether that be Zoom, Microsoft Teams, Google Meet, or somewhere else. After that, I'll walk you through defining your preferences. For example, do you want a buffer before or after new meetings so your meetings aren't back-to-back? The last thing I'm going to cover is getting you set up with the Chrome extension so that you can easily leverage Apollo Meetings in your inbox as well.

Now, a quick note: Meetings is currently only compatible with Google accounts and Microsoft accounts, and you can only connect one calendar per user. So, let's get to it.

From the home screen, click on Meetings under "Win and Close." You'll see a screen pop up with a big blue button that says "Connect Your Calendar." Let's click that. Now you're going to see a screen asking you which calendar you want to connect. You can only connect one, and it has to be a Google or Microsoft account. It will default to your login for Apollo, but you can always change that. Just make sure it's the right calendar for your work meetings, and we'll hit "Connect."

This is where you'll set your defaults and preferences. The first one up is your default availability across your calendar week. It's going to set itself from 9 AM to 5 PM, Monday through Friday, in your local time zone, but you can make any adjustments. If, on Friday, you're available from 9 to noon, you can set that here. And if you need to break up the day, you can always hit this plus sign and change the times to account for that. So, potentially, it's 9 AM to 10:30 AM and then 2 PM to 5 PM.

Next, we're going to want to set if we want a buffer before or after a meeting. It will block off time before or after so that you can let the meeting run long or have time to prep. This way, you're not in a situation where your meetings end and start at the same time. I like to set a little bit of a buffer afterward. Most of my meetings are new business, so if they go long, that's a good thing for me. I'd like to make sure I can do that.

After you set up your before and after buffers, you'll tell Apollo what your minimum scheduling notice needs to be. For me, I don't want any meetings coming on my calendar with less notice than four hours. I need to prep for these. I want to be impressive and give myself the best chances of closing that deal.

Next, you're going to set your default meeting location. Hit that dropdown, and you can select from Google Meet, Zoom, Microsoft Teams, or a custom meeting link that will allow you to use anything that isn't integrated with Apollo. I'm going to select Google Meet and hit "Continue."

Once you're done with that, you'll be taken to a screen where you'll see your default meeting types that have been created for you, either by the administrator or available by default from Apollo. From here, let's click on "Availability and Tools."

From this screen, you can connect multiple places to meet. You'll notice I've already got Google Meet connected, but I could also integrate with Zoom and Microsoft Teams at the same time and use different platforms for different types of meetings. Scroll down, and you'll see an area called "Custom Branding." This is where you can upload a logo that will feature prominently on your meeting landing pages.

Lastly, you're going to want to make sure you have the Apollo Chrome extension. You'll see the page for it right here. If you don't have it installed, the link is in the resource kit. Click that and get it set up so that you can take advantage of using Meetings directly in your inbox. You'll see I've got a new email right here. You'll be able to click "Meetings," easily insert the right meeting link when you're sending an email or replying to someone. It makes it really simple and very convenient.

That's the end of setting up Meetings in your Apollo account. Join me in the next video, where I'm going to show you how to create your custom meeting links.
`},{title:"Creating custom links",wistiaId:"i1nidngzxe",length:"7:36",description:(0,a.jsxs)("div",{className:"space-y-6",children:[(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{variant:"h5",children:"In this lesson, you'll learn how to use Apollo Meetings to set up custom meeting links that cater to various scheduling needs—from single-host to multi-host to round-robin."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"James will also cover how to automate email reminders to reduce no-shows and customize intake forms for better meeting preparation."})]}),deepLink:{heading:"Like what you're learning?",linkText:"Do it in Apollo",url:"https://app.apollo.io"},transcript:`In this course, we're going to walk through how to set up and use Apollo Meetings. 

Meetings empowers your prospects to schedule with you and get on your calendar in seconds. Instead of the back-and-forth emails trying to find a time that works for everyone, your prospects will simply click a link, pick a time that suits them, and be done with it.

Getting Meetings set up brings a host of improvements. It streamlines scheduling for all your meeting types, whether they’re with you or rotating through other team members. It encourages proactive engagement for new or repeat customers, making it easy for them to get on your calendar and move business forward. It reduces the risk of no-shows with automated reminders and an easy reschedule link in the original invite and reminder emails. Additionally, it allows you to consolidate tools. Remember, Apollo is an all-in-one sales platform, and Meetings is built right in. You don’t need to search for a third-party tool—it’s already there, easy to set up, and can save you money. Furthermore, it allows you to automate meeting activities. Since it's integrated, you can tie it together with other parts of Apollo, such as automating workflows. Maybe you want to create a deal every time a new meeting is booked. You can set that up using Apollo Meetings. 

It might seem like a small thing here, but it actually drives a really big impact. It's going to help you drive more revenue and free up time for both you and your prospects, giving them a much better experience.

All of this works by integrating your calendar with Apollo and then creating custom meeting links. That’s what we’ll cover in this course. 

First, we'll set you up with Meetings. We'll connect your calendar and choose a default meeting location, whether it’s Zoom, Google Meet, Microsoft Teams, or some other platform. 

Then we’ll cover creating custom meeting links — so you can adjust the host situation, the availability of your calendar, and even where the meeting should take place.

After that I’ll show you how you can use your new meeting links both in and outside Apollo.

And in the final video, we’ll make the prepwork for those meetings a breeze by using AI-powered pre-meeting insights.

Join me in the next video, where I'll walk you through getting everything set up. You’ll be set up with Apollo Meetings in just a few minutes.
`},{title:"Integrating Meetings into your workflow",wistiaId:"aome2xfmly",length:"5:36",description:(0,a.jsxs)("div",{className:"space-y-6",children:[(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{variant:"h5",children:"Time to seamlessly weave Apollo Meetings into your daily routine and keep your calendar running like a well-oiled machine."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"In this lesson, you’ll discover how to:"}),(0,a.jsx)(i.A,{color:"purple",items:["Turn your email signature and LinkedIn profile into powerful booking tools","Craft exclusive meeting links for your VIP leads","Unleash the full potential of the Apollo Chrome extension right from your inbox","And more!"]})]}),deepLink:{heading:"Like what you're learning?",linkText:"Do it in Apollo",url:"https://app.apollo.io"},transcript:`In this video, we're going to tie it all together. I'll hop into Apollo and show you how to integrate Meetings into your workflow.

We'll cover where you can put and use your meeting links, both for active and passive situations. We'll look at how to use your meeting links with priority leads, your VIP prospects. Then, I'll demonstrate how to use the Apollo Chrome extension to bring the power of Apollo Meetings directly into your inbox. We'll also discuss best practices so you can maximize the results you get from using your meeting links.

So, we’re at the home screen. The first two things I want to do are: put a link to book time with me in my signature for all the emails going out through Apollo and add a link on LinkedIn to make it easy for people to book time with me from there as well. 

I’ll start by clicking on Meetings. I’ll take my thirty-minute meeting link, which is for general-purpose customer meetings, and add it to my signature. To do this, click on "Settings," then "Manage Mailboxes," and click the three dots next to your mailbox. Go to "Check Mailbox Health."

This will take you through the mailbox configuration, just like when you initially linked it. The first option in that mailbox configuration is "Signature." I’ll make the link here. That looks good.

Now, for the link on LinkedIn, I’ve created a fifteen-minute meeting. The only change from my other links is that I’ve added a fifteen-minute buffer at the end so that if someone is coming in because they’re not qualified, I limit my exposure to fifteen minutes. However, if the meeting is promising, it can go longer. So, I’ve got my fifteen-minute quick meetup meeting. I’ll go to LinkedIn and add it there.

Some people put it in their bio, and I’ve seen others put a button up here. You can do this by clicking "Custom Button" and then selecting "Link." Pop that in, and you’re all set.

The next thing I want to do is create a new meeting type for my best leads, like VIP leads. So, I'll create a new meeting type here. I’ll name it "Priority Meeting," set it to thirty minutes, and continue. This will just be for me.

I’ll edit the working hours from my normal work week because, for the leads I’d send this to, I’d be willing to meet at almost any time they want. For the schedule notice for VIPs, I’ll set it to one minute, just so I’m not late. For the meeting buffer, I’ll set it to fifteen minutes to have a cushion and turn on the email reminder.

Great. Now I have my priority meeting link with extended calendar availability. I’m going to use this link in a sequence for a follow-up email. I’ve got a VIP sequence here—mostly phone calls and some LinkedIn messages—but I’ll add an email and include that calendar link as a way to book with me. I’ve got one more thing to do: reply to a couple of folks and get them a meeting link so we can get scheduled.

If you don’t have the Apollo Chrome extension, make sure to install and set it up. It will allow you to bring not only Meetings but other Apollo features into your inbox as well. 

I have a few emails in a folder here that I need to get back to. Here’s someone who wants to bring their sales leaders with them. I’ll include my calendar link below.

To include your meeting link, click on Meetings and then pick the one you want to use. You can copy the link to the clipboard, insert it as a link, or choose preferred meeting times by clicking the little calendar icon. I want to send them a thirty-minute meeting and would like to schedule it for tomorrow afternoon if possible.

I’ll reserve that slot. This will be my preferred meeting time, which will now be reserved on my calendar if that works for them. They can still see the rest of my availability, but it will default to that one right off the bat, and I’ll send it.

Once you start booking some meetings, you’ll want to make sure you’re well prepped for them — Meetings can help you there too with AI-powered pre-meeting insights. So join me in the next video where I’ll show you how to make it really easy to be well researched and prepped ahead of that big meeting.
`},{title:"Using pre-meeting insights",wistiaId:"98h7hcqlb0",length:"2:52",description:(0,a.jsxs)("div",{className:"space-y-6",children:[(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{variant:"h5",children:"Preparing for meetings is just as important as booking them."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"In this lesson, you’ll learn how to use Apollo’s AI-powered pre-meeting insights to ensure you're ready for any conversation with tailored, actionable information."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"You'll learn how to:"}),(0,a.jsx)(i.A,{color:"purple",items:["Access and run pre-meeting insight templates","Edit pre-meeting prompts for specific needs","Associate insights with records like meetings, deals, or contacts","Find and use saved insights to stay organized and well-prepared"]})]}),deepLink:{heading:"Like what you're learning?",linkText:"Do it in Apollo",url:"https://app.apollo.io"},transcript:`It's great making it easy for people to book time with you and get on your calendar. But once those meetings are booked, you've gotta be prepped for them.

AI-powered pre-meeting insights — that's what we're gonna cover in this video. I'm going to show you how to find and use pre-meeting insights on your upcoming meetings, how to associate these pre-meeting insights with various records such as meetings, conversations, deals, contacts, or companies, and where you can find these insights in notes whenever you need them. 

So hop into your Apollo account if you'd like to follow along. Let's get to it.

We're at the home screen. Let's go click on "Meetings" on that navigation column.

Once you're in the "Meetings" sub, just make sure you're looking at all meetings and your upcoming ones. I've got a big meeting tomorrow I want to make sure I'm prepped for. Now you'll see at the edge of all your meetings that are coming up, a little button that says "Insights."

Click that, and you'll see “Meeting prep templates” popping up. These are pre-built, pre-meeting insight prompts that you can use to learn about the person, the company, or to research outside of Apollo data so you're well prepared.

I'm going to select "Get overview on meeting attendees" and "Summarize key company information." You can run one or multiple at the same time. And if you want to edit any of the prompts for that specific instance, just hit the arrow down and go to "Edit Template."

Once you've got the ones you want, hit "Run for All," and you'll see something that slides out from the side. This will show you the homework it's doing, and you can actually see it up here by hitting these little tabs.

Below that, you'll see an area to associate that research with various records. You can select a person, a company, deals, meetings, as well as your recorded conversations if you want it to be attached there. I've got mine all set up.

So I'll just hit "Save Note." Once that note is saved, you can close out of there. It's really easy to find the information that comes from the pre-meeting insights that you run. I'm going to click on the meeting and just scroll down, and you'll notice there's a “Notes” field.

In fact, there's the notes that were just created one minute ago from the two pre-meeting insight templates I ran. I'll click on there, and here's my overview of all the meeting attendees as well as the company information I was looking for. If you want to associate that with new records, you can continue to do so right down here, and you'll be able to find that information directly attached to any of those records from elsewhere in the platform by clicking on "Notes" in those records.

And that concludes our Learn Apollo course on how to set up and use Meetings. Thanks for joining us. Happy selling!
`}],x=[{title:"Intro to Workflows",shortDescription:"",wistiaId:"a59ephi2l0",length:"1:12",deepLink:{heading:"Find and close your next deal in Apollo",url:"/sign-up",linkText:"Sign up for free",extraPadding:!0},description:(0,a.jsxs)(n.A,{spacing:3,children:[(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{variant:"h5",children:"Workflows is a tool in Apollo that lets you build end-to-end automations in a single, intuitive view. Automations that can save you time, expand your reach, and scale your business."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"In this lesson, James will introduce you to the core functionality of Apollo Workflows — what it is and why it’s a gamechanger."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"You’ll see just how easy it is to begin automating your sales process and setting yourself up for greater sales success."})]}),transcript:`In this course, we're gonna learn how to build automations in Apollo using workflows.

Workflows is an Apollo feature that lets you build powerful end to end automations in a single view with an easy user experience. Automations that can save time, expand your reach, and multiply your potential impact on the business. And that impact can be big. Customers sending outreach emails are booking thirty percent more meetings when they're leveraging workflow automations. You can use workflows to automate fundamental tasks of your selling process, like adding contacts to a sequence or list, scheduling tasks for yourself or your reps, or sending alerts to you or other people on the team when something important has happened. Workflows can transform the way you work and sell, and that's important because seventy percent of sellers say that this year, selling has gotten more difficult than last year. You will be surprised at how easy it is to build powerful automations.

You tell Apollo what you want to happen.

Go get me new leads that meet my ICP, my ideal persona, and save them every week. When you want it to happen, such as every week on Monday or when a trigger event occurs, something happens, and with whom, leveraging all the filters and data in Apollo to make sure your automation is only happening when the situation is right. So if you want Apollo to look for new marketing director leads in Chicago every week at companies from five to five hundred employees that use Google Workspace and have verified emails to save them and put them into a sequence, you can do that. This course will get you ready to build workflows for a variety of situations.

First, we're gonna build a simple task automation, something that removes those time intensive tasks from your plate. Then we're gonna build a trigger based workflow, something that only happens when the time is right. And the last one we're gonna build is an advanced multi branch workflow. So you can handle the situation differently depending on what you want to have happen or what's best for the business. At the end of this course, you're gonna have your first three automations built out, and you'll know how to create more. So join me in the next video where we're gonna build our first automation, a simple task automation. We're gonna have it go look for more of our perfect leads every week and then save them to a list for us.
`},{title:"Simple task automation workflows",shortDescription:"",wistiaId:"itxf1en4yy",length:"4:08",deepLink:{heading:"Like what you’re learning?",url:"https://app.apollo.io/#/workflows",linkText:"Use Workflows in Apollo",extraPadding:!0},description:(0,a.jsxs)(n.A,{spacing:3,children:[(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{variant:"h5",children:"Fed up with those tedious, repetitive tasks that eat up your day? Let’s automate them."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"In this lesson, you’ll create your first workflow — a simple automation to find your ideal leads every week, save them to a list, and add them to a sequence — all with minimal effort on your part."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"Sounds too good to be true? Watch and find out. You’ll learn how to:"}),(0,a.jsx)(i.A,{items:[(0,a.jsxs)(a.Fragment,{children:["Use"," ",(0,a.jsx)(h,{href:"https://app.apollo.io/#/workflow-templates/66df7cc7d7a8080001098909",children:"Workflow templates"})," ","to quickly build game-changing automations"]}),"Automatically target perfect-fit leads every week & add them to a sequence","Set up enrollment criteria and other filters, such as buying intent","Adjust settings to account for re-enrollments, approvals, & more","Track and refine your workflow’s performance using Apollo’s intuitive dashboards"],color:"purple"})]}),transcript:`Let's start things off with a simple task automation workflow, something that can move a lot of busy work from our plate.

We're gonna build a workflow that's gonna go in and find our ideal leads every week, and it's gonna get the right amount of them and put them into a list and a matching sequence. So hop into your Apollo account. Let's build this together.

So we're at the home screen. Let's go build that workflow together. You'll notice there's a workflows button on that navigation column. Let's click there.

We're gonna use a workflow template to make this first one really easy.

Just click on workflow templates and find the one that says prospect good fit ICPs.

When you hit try it, it's gonna pull this up giving you an overview of what it's gonna do.

Hit use template, and it'll get you started. The first screen is gonna ask you to personalize the template by including details about your customer's pain points, what your value prop is, what you bring to the table, and if you have a meeting link to pop it in here as well. If you don't have one, you could set up Apollo meetings, and we have a course on that. Then you'll have an easy way for people to book time on your calendar. I'm going to pop mine in, and we'll hit save and continue. The

first box you'll see at the top says, when this happens.

Click on that box, and you'll be able to choose when this automation should run and the enrollment criteria, what leads you're looking for.

I'm gonna have this start immediately after activation, and it'll run every week on

Friday. Now I've got to tell Apollo what leads I'm looking for. Scroll down to enrollment criteria and hit edit filters.

You'll notice you can use your personas here. I've got mine already loaded up. But I wanna include another signal as well, And I only want to grab the net new leads, ones I've never saved or worked before.

Hit save trigger when you're done setting when this automation should run and your enrollment criteria. You'll notice that there's a section of this workflow under a title of then do this, add to contact list, and add contacts to sequence.

Every week, it's gonna find those new leads that meet your enrollment criteria and then add them to the list that you'd like them to be part of, and then add them to the sequence you want them to be part of.

Once you're done there, check the enrollment criteria and the list in sequence. Let's make sure everything looks good. If it does, go

to the top and click on settings right next to that workflow tab. The first option here is giving your workflow a name. Give yourself clarity at a glance so so you're never confused about what it was doing. You could add more details by hitting this tab right here and giving it a description or putting it in a folder if you wanna keep them organized.

Below that, you'll see customization options where you can choose what's the maximum amount of leads you want to save and put into the list in a sequence every week.

I've got mine set to fifty, but depending on how many mailboxes you've got and what these leads are, you might wanna adjust that. Additionally, you could set it to reenroll people or not. Do you want it to be able to find the same leads and put them back into the sequence? In mine, it's gonna be only net new leads and once.

At the bottom, you'll see approval, automatic or manual. That's gonna tell the workflow, grab the leads and put them in these list and sequences on its own, or do you wanna be able to approve all the leads it's picked and give a thumbs up before it goes through with it? I'm going to do automatic on this one, and I'm going to hit save. If everything's looking good, you can turn your workflow on right up here with this toggle.

If your workflow is saved, you can go back to the dashboard,

and you'll see that it's turned on here. And when you click into it again, you're going to be taken to an overview page telling you what it's been doing. You'll see the number of contacts at the top, any that are active or failed. You can click back into the workflow editor if you wanna make changes in the future.

Of course, you can update the settings, but you'll notice a couple new tabs. You've got enrollment here where you'll see the leads it's grabbed as part of your workflow. You can see your tasks and activity as part of this workflow as well. Congrats. You've now finished your first simple task automation.
`},{title:"Trigger-based workflows",shortDescription:"",wistiaId:"94l3w2syyk",length:"5:01",deepLink:{heading:"Like what you’re learning?",url:"https://app.apollo.io/#/workflows",linkText:"Use Workflows in Apollo",extraPadding:!0},description:(0,a.jsxs)(n.A,{spacing:3,children:[(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{variant:"h5",children:"The best sellers in the world know how to act fast when the timing’s right."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"In this lesson, you’ll discover how to create trigger-based automations that let you engage with prospects the moment they show interest — so you never miss a hot opportunity again."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"You’ll learn how to:"}),(0,a.jsx)(i.A,{items:["Build trigger-based workflows from scratch","Set up triggers for specific events, like when an email is opened","Filter workflows to focus on high-value leads or specific personas","Assign tasks like LinkedIn interactions, phone calls, or emails","Use dynamic variables to personalize LinkedIn messages effortlessly"],color:"purple"})]}),transcript:`We just learned how to build a simple linear workflow.

But what about those situations where the automation should only occur when something else happens?

In this video, we're gonna give ourselves great timing because this automation's gonna look for something else to happen. In this case, when one of our VIP contacts opens one of our emails from a sequence. Then we're gonna tell Apollo to go create a task for us to interact with them on LinkedIn or to give them a phone call. So hop into your Apollo account, and let's build it together.

So we're at the home screen. Let's go back to workflows. Let's build that trigger based workflow.

Click on workflows on the navigation column, and let's go up to create workflow.

And we're gonna create from scratch this time. It's a lot easier than you think, though the templates are great.

The first thing we're gonna have to do is add a trigger.

When should this happen?

You can choose a date or a schedule or a trigger event. In this case, let's do trigger event.

You'll notice you can set up trigger events to be on people, companies, or deals. We're gonna go with people.

Hit the event drop down, and let's scroll down to email opened.

When somebody's looking at email recently saw, it's a great time to double tap, whether it's interacting on LinkedIn or making a call.

You'll notice that down here, you can choose what sequences it's looking at. I'm gonna do all of mine, and I only want this set up for myself.

Below that, you'll see your enrollment criteria. Should this happen for everybody or just certain leads? I'm gonna choose my best leads, my VIP leads. You could hit edit filters right here, and I'm gonna use a persona, though all the filters are available.

Once you've identified when you want this to happen and with who, hit save trigger.

You'll see there's a box for then do this. This is where you're gonna tell Apollo what do you wanna happen when that trigger is activated.

You'll see a variety of actions on the right side of your screen. Drag and drop it over.

In this case,

I wanna assign manual task.

Let's click on it so we can tell it what task to do. You'll notice you can create a contact task, an account task, or create a deal task. I want this to be a contact task since that's what we're looking for.

For task type, you can choose an email, phone call, LinkedIn interaction, an action item. I'm gonna go with LinkedIn interaction. I'm gonna try to either message them on LinkedIn at that time or maybe interact with some of their posts. I'm gonna default to message though, and I'll assign it to myself.

You'll notice you can pop in the LinkedIn message here. If you want to make things really easy, you can actually put in your dynamic variables here, so it'll be personalized and ready to go.

And that's it. We've got our trigger. We know when it's gonna happen, and we're gonna create that task. Just hit save.

And now your workflow is ready to turn on.
`},{title:"Multi-branch workflows",shortDescription:"",wistiaId:"1jsovo7s7f",length:"5:25",deepLink:{heading:"Like what you’re learning?",url:"https://app.apollo.io/#/workflows",linkText:"Use Workflows in Apollo",extraPadding:!0},description:(0,a.jsxs)(n.A,{spacing:3,children:[(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{variant:"h5",children:"What if your workflows could think like you — adapting to every lead’s unique traits and needs?"}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"This lesson shows you how to build dynamic, multi-path automations that tailor your outreach for maximum impact."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"You’ll learn how to:"}),(0,a.jsx)(i.A,{items:["Segment leads based on personas and data filters","Create specific sequences for leads with and without phone numbers","Set up workflows for manual approval","Navigate settings, review pending tasks, and analyze activity history","And more!"],color:"purple"})]}),transcript:`We now know how to build simple task automations and trigger based ones as well. That'll take care of a huge chunk of all the automations we'd wanna set up, but not all.

Sometimes there are a variety of ways we'd want to handle a situation. So that's what we're going to take care of. We're going to build a multi branch workflow together.

Automations that can take a variety of paths. We're going to build an automation that's gonna save leads from a few different personas, and it's gonna break them up. The ones with phone numbers will go into sequences where we're gonna make a call. The ones without go into sequences where there's no calls. So hop into your Apollo account. I'm gonna hop into mine. Let's do it together.

So we're at the home screen. Let's go click on workflows, of course, and we're gonna build that multi branch workflow together. Now, I'm gonna use personas. I already have a few different ones set up. If you're not using personas, it's an easy way to save the basic building blocks of the different types of people you want to sell to. It's a great way to filter them.

So let's hit create workflow and go from scratch.

And let's start with the when this happens, where we add our trigger at the top. Just click on that box, and you could choose trigger event or date or schedule. I'm going to do a schedule. It's going to run every week.

And then let's hit our filters at the bottom.

Now I mentioned I was going to use persona. If If you don't have any, you can hit plus persona here and build them out. But I'm going to select my sales leaders SMB, sales leaders mid markets, and then I'm going to add email status as well so that I'm getting only the leads where we've got a verified email.

Once you got that filled out, let's hit save trigger.

Now I wanna save those.

I wanna get them all saved and organized because I wanna use some of the details of those leads to determine what sequences they should go into.

So I'm gonna add multi split right here.

Well, there's gonna be two branches. Just click on the multi split branch when you pull it over. Branch one will be sales leaders SMB.

Sales editors, and then markets.

You click add filters underneath them, and that's where you're going to choose what filters it's looking for to determine what path it goes down. For me, I'm going to do my one persona going there and the other one going here.

Perfect.

Now that will allow me to choose what list those leads are getting saved to. You'll notice on the side here, you can drag and drop for the variety of options. I'm gonna do manage lists.

Again, you just click on the box, choose what you want to happen.

I'll select the right list and save. And I'll do the same for my other path right here.

And this else here, I'm not sure what that could be, but some you never know. I'm just gonna have it exit.

Now I've got the lead saved. Now I wanna put them in the right sequences, but the ones with phone numbers, I wanna go into sequences where I'm making phone calls, the ones without into a different sequence. So I wanna make sure that after those leads are saved, I'm filtering them based on if they have a phone number amount. The ones that do should go into a sequence just for those types of leads where I'm calling and the ones that don't in another. So drag over true false branch and drop it right on that plus sign in that same path as where you just saved it into lists. You'll see true false. You define it by clicking on that box and add the filter.

In this case, I'm going to look for phone status.

Contact has a phone number, and I only want mobiles, work, and corporate.

Now the ones with the phone number I wanna call, I've got sequences built up for that, so I'm gonna drag over manage sequences to both of these.

So the ones with a phone number will get assigned to the sequence with calls, and the one without will go to the sequence with no calls.

Now we'll do the same with our other persona. You could do this for more than just two, of course.

I'm gonna drag over true false branch And do the same thing with phone numbers.

Mobile work and corporate.

Now I'm gonna have those go into their own sequences.

I generally put a little bit more effort, more steps in my sequences for these leads because it's a bit more opportunity in them.

Again, click on the other one here for the false branch so it can go into the right sequence.

So now we've got two different personas being broken up depending on the qualifications of those leads. In my case, it's phone number. All of them have clean emails, but you can do that with any of the data and the filters available to you here.

I'm gonna save this, and let's go over to settings as well.

I'm gonna update the title here so that I know what it's looking to do. I'm gonna set a max amount of people based on how many mailboxes I have.

Only once for reenrollment.

And on these, because they're my highest priority leads, generally speaking, I'm gonna do manual approval.

That'll put a task for me in workflows to approve the context it's about to throw in. I'm gonna hit save, and I'm gonna turn it on.

Now once you turn that workflow on, it's saved, it's activated.

You'll notice that you've got more tabs showing up on that workflow. Of course, you have your overview, your workflow, which you can continue to edit if you'd like, settings, enrollments where you'll see all the people that have enrolled in that workflow.

If you set manual approval, you'll see that when you go to task. You'll see workflow review pending, and it'll show up here should your workflow have gone through and pulled contacts.

Lastly, you'll see activity at the end where you can see anything that's happened on this workflow and the history of how that workflow has been running. Congratulations.

Now you know how to build simple task automations, trigger based workflows, and how to handle multiple branches as well. You're ready to start building all the automations you need and turbocharging the way you sell. Good luck and happy selling.
`}],j=[{title:"Intro to AI Research",shortDescription:"",wistiaId:"n3wmh3n67e",length:"2:28",deepLink:{heading:"Like what you’re learning?",url:"https://app.apollo.io/?#/people?page=1&sortAscending=false&sortByField=%5Bnone%5D&prospectedByCurrentTeam[]=yes&powerupTemplateModal=open",linkText:"Use AI Research Prompts in Apollo",extraPadding:!0},description:(0,a.jsxs)(n.A,{spacing:3,children:[(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{variant:"h5",children:"Say hello to AI Research Prompts — a feature in Apollo that takes your sales prospecting and outreach to the next level by leveraging artificial intelligence."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"In this lesson, James will introduce you to AI Research Prompts and the three AI models available for you to use on Apollo: AI Search Engine, AI Text Generator, and AI Copywriter."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"You’ll learn how to:"}),(0,a.jsx)(i.A,{items:["Understand how AI Research Prompts work","Learn about the three AI models available on Apollo","Explore the benefits of using AI Research Prompts for sales prospecting"],color:"purple"})]}),transcript:`This course covers how to use AI Research to turbocharge your selling in Apollo.

Research are AI-powered insights into both people and companies that can accelerate research you'd normally be doing on prospects or help you personalize your outbound messaging.

AI and automation are changing the face of sales — and it's easy to see why. Apollo customers that leverage AI Research and automations book 47% more meetings.

Research use Apollo data and external data, along with AI, to uncover and reveal the most important details about your prospects. These insights are generated using one of three AI models:

AI Search Engine: Best for researching and prospecting leads at scale, delivering quick insights on people or companies you can use to improve your targeting.

AI Text Generator: Best for targeting, categorizing, or summarizing both Apollo data and information from other AI Research.

AI Copywriter: Best for generating messaging using the information you've acquired inside Apollo. Use it to create personalized emails, ad hoc LinkedIn messages, or scripts and notes for upcoming meetings and pitches.

AI Research are extremely powerful, but they're also really easy to use. You can write your own custom prompts using any of the three AI engines, or you can use Apollo's prebuilt Research, available in your account right now.

This course will get you ready to start using AI Research in your sales process. Over the next three videos, we're going to:

1. Improve your targeting by using a Research to research your leads and get the information you need to truly understand if a prospect is a good fit.

2. Personalize your outreach by researching your top leads and summarizing the findings on the record, just like you would if you were conducting the research yourself.

3. Generate messaging by leveraging AI to research and craft highly personalized emails.

So, let’s get to it. Let’s use an AI Research together!
`},{title:"Improving your targeting",shortDescription:"",wistiaId:"jogm7n1i9x",length:"4:46",deepLink:{heading:"Like what you’re learning?",url:"https://app.apollo.io/?#/people?page=1&sortAscending=false&sortByField=%5Bnone%5D&prospectedByCurrentTeam[]=yes&powerupTemplateModal=open",linkText:"Use AI Research in Apollo",extraPadding:!0},description:(0,a.jsxs)(n.A,{spacing:3,children:[(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{variant:"h5",children:"Tired of wasting time hunting for the right leads? Let AI Research Prompts do the heavy lifting."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"In this lesson, you’ll learn how to update your AI Content Center and use prebuilt templates to streamline your targeting process, saving you time and effort."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"You’ll learn how to:"}),(0,a.jsx)(i.A,{items:["Set up your AI Content Center with company, product, and customer details to supercharge AI insights","Select and customize an AI Research Prompt template to find perfect-fit leads.","Use AI-generated fields to personalize your outreach and create dynamic workflows","And more!"],color:"purple"})]}),transcript:`Let’s start things off by getting a power-up to research our leads for us.

Apollo has a lot of data, but oftentimes, there are additional details, data, something that we need that we’ve gotta go find manually or that we wish we had that would allow us to better understand our leads or to prioritize or identify the right ones.

So that’s what we’re gonna do in this video. We’re gonna improve our targeting. The first thing we’re gonna do is we’re gonna hop into Apollo together and update our AI Content Center. That’s where we can give Apollo details to understand what we sell, what we do, what we bring to the table.

Then we’re gonna go grab ten of our saved leads and put them into a list. Those are gonna be the ones that we run our AI Research on. And then we’re gonna select a power-up from the "Built by Apollo" templates in the "Improve Your Targeting" category.

So hop into your Apollo account with me. Let’s do this together, and pause if you need more time.

So I’m at the home screen. Hopefully, you are too. The first thing we’re gonna do is go set up our AI Content Center.

First, you’ll click Settings at the bottom left. There’s a lot of settings in Apollo. You can find anything you’re looking for just by going to the search box. In this case, you could just type “Content,” and you’ll see AI Content Center there.

Now this is where you put in information about your company, your product, your value prop, customer pain points, even your competitors. You preload this all in here to help inform the AI so it can do a better job of finding the right leads, identifying information, generating messaging.

You’ll see there’s a number of fields here. Do the best you can to put them in there. I’ve already filled most of it out. If you wanna start with what it can pull from your website, just hit the dropdown right here and pop in your company website.

Once it looks good, let’s hit Save, and we’ll go back to the home screen.

Now we’re gonna run this Research on just ten leads to get started. We’re gonna go grab some new ones and put them into a list so it’s really easy to see what those Research are generating.

First, you’ll click People on the side. If you already got a few leads you wanna use that are saved, that’s great. I’m gonna grab some new ones using a persona I’ve created. Let’s put those leads into a list so it’s easy to find everything we’ve done in this course.

So let’s go load up our list where we’ve got ten leads we’re gonna use for this Research.

Go up to that top-right button that says Research, and you’ll see two options there: View Templates or Run Your Custom AI Prompt. Of course, you can write your own, copy it over from another platform.

Well, let’s go View Templates. And then we’re gonna do an "Improve Your Targeting" template here. You’ll see a few different options available from Apollo. Now these are a great way to simplify or remove work that you normally have to go do manually.

In my case, I’m gonna do "Assign as B2B or B2C." I really only go outbound for B2B opportunities. I’ll take B2C if it’s inbound, but not gonna go outbound for it. So I’m gonna use that one. But review all of them, see which one’s gonna be best for you.

Once you hit Try It, you’ll see this pop-up where it’s gonna show you the engine it’s gonna be using — in this case, AI text generator — and you’ll see the full prompt it’s using as well.

If you scroll down, you’ll see all the field settings. Field Name is what it’s gonna auto-assign to that field. If you wanna change it, you can pop it in there. I’m gonna simplify it.

And then you can choose the Field Type: single-line text, multiline, or pick list. In this case, I’m just gonna go with pick list. That’s what it defaulted to because there’s only really a couple options.

Below that, you’ll see how you wanna save the field: global or private. Global, of course, all the users on your account can see it. Private, just you.

Once it looks good, let’s hit Save and Run.

Once our Research is done running, you’ll notice that there’s a new field added to the data on these records. It’ll be the name that you gave it when you ran the Research, and you’ll see that it has broken down those ten leads — B2B or B2C. Now that is a field on the record, so you can use that as a dynamic variable in your emails or sequences should that information be useful there.

And, of course, you can use it to set up multi-branch workflows as well.

So now we’ve got our AI Content Center updated, and we’ve run our first Research. But I’d like to remove some additional work from my plan. That’s what we’re gonna do in the next video.

We’re gonna use a Research to go research our leads, summarize everything it’s finding, take those notes, and put them on the records so we can personalize our outreach.
`},{title:"Researching leads",shortDescription:"",wistiaId:"cp6gr0n8g9",length:"4:41",deepLink:{heading:"Like what you’re learning?",url:"https://app.apollo.io/?#/people?page=1&sortAscending=false&sortByField=%5Bnone%5D&prospectedByCurrentTeam[]=yes&powerupTemplateModal=opens",linkText:"Use AI Research in Apollo",extraPadding:!0},description:(0,a.jsxs)(n.A,{spacing:3,children:[(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{variant:"h5",children:"Join James as he dives into how to use AI Research Prompts to do deep-dive research on leads and automate your outreach like a pro."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"You’ll discover how to save time, boost productivity, and skip the boring manual stuff so you can focus on the leads that really matter."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"By the end of this lesson, you’ll be able to:"}),(0,a.jsx)(i.A,{items:["Use AI Research Prompts to gather insights about prospects from LinkedIn","Automate outreach with sequences based on their online activity","Apply true/false branches in Workflows to automatically sort leads","And more!"],color:"purple"})]}),transcript:`So we just used a Research to go get new data — new information about our leads. Now, I'm going to use a Research to research my leads in a much deeper way.

I’m going to use a Research to track down details about the contact or company and then summarize it and put it on the record for us. In my case, it’s going to let me spend more time on the leads where I have more information to use, and I’m actually going to automate how to handle the ones where I don’t.

So in this video, we’re going to go back to our list. We’re going to use one of the built by Apollo templated Research in the Personalize Your Outreach category. Then, I’ll show you how I’m using my Research in my automations. I’m going to use the details that come from the research we’re about to do to automate which leads go into which sequence.

So hop into your Apollo account, and let’s do this together.

Let’s go back to the leads we were just using in the last video, and we’ll run another Research on them. This time, instead of going to get data, we’re going to have it research those contacts.

Click the Research button at the top right and select Start with a Template. This time, we’re going to do Personalize Your Outreach. This is where a Research goes and deep researches your contacts or companies and grabs that information and puts it on the record. In this case, I’m going to do Summarize Professional Posts.

If they’re posting a lot, if they’re active on LinkedIn, I’d like to put those into a sequence where I’m manually writing that first email and using that information. If they’re not, then I’m going to put them into a different sequence where it’s going to start with an automated email.

So there are quite a few options here. Choose the one that’s going to get the information most useful for you. Again, I’m going to do Summarize Professional Posts.

Now you’ll see the breakdown, the configuration of that Research. On mine, it’s got two steps. It’s not only going to go look to see if they are posting and grab those posts, but it’s also going to summarize them for me, collate all that information together.

To the left, you’ll see a preview window where it’s going to show you the results for a couple of your leads to see if this is what you want it to do. In this case, for this lead, it shows No posts found in the last two months. That’s exactly what I want it to do. If that person’s not posting, let me know about it. If everything looks good, let’s run this on the leads.

Once your Research is activated, it’s going to create those new fields at the end of the list. If you want to move them to the front, prioritize them more, click View Options, and I’m going to move the new fields that were just created to the top.

As you can see, it’s gone to see if they’ve been posting. Some of these have none; some of them have quite a few posts. Then here’s the full summary. It can be a little bit condensed, tighter, hard to see in the search results screen, but all this information is stored in Custom Fields on the contact. Just click on somebody’s name, and at the top of the screen, you’ll notice it has a breakdown of the contact — what sequences, deals, conversations, or meetings you’ve had with that person — and Custom Fields. Click Custom Fields, and you’ll see all the custom fields associated with that record and the details within.

So I’m going to pop over to a workflow I’ve already got created. I’m just going to do a quick edit to show you how you can do this.

I’m going to add a True/False Branch. This is a workflow that is grabbing leads from that list and putting them into a sequence. Now I’m going to break it up.

Click on the True/False Branch. It’s going to look for the ones with LinkedIn activity.

Now hit Add Filters to tell it how to break these leads up, and you’ll notice that Custom Fields — the ones created by yourself or Research — are available as a filtering mechanism.

I can say find all the ones that have posts on LinkedIn. In this case, it’s six of the ten, and drop those into a sequence that I’ll treat differently than the ones that don’t.

Now I’ve got a Research not only getting me that information but allowing me to set up Workflows that are really going to save me a lot of time.
`},{title:"Generating personalized emails",shortDescription:"",wistiaId:"znlq4l3hin",length:"5:03",deepLink:{heading:"Like what you’re learning?",url:"https://app.apollo.io/?#/people?page=1&sortAscending=false&sortByField=%5Bnone%5D&prospectedByCurrentTeam[]=yes&powerupTemplateModal=open",linkText:"Use AI Research in Apollo",extraPadding:!0},description:(0,a.jsxs)(n.A,{spacing:3,children:[(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{variant:"h5",children:"What if you could send perfectly personalized emails without spending hours on research and copywriting?"}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"This lesson explores how Apollo’s AI Research Prompts can help you craft hyper-personalized messages using AI and real-time data — so you can engage your leads more effectively with less manual effort."}),(0,a.jsx)(s.A,{children:"You’ll learn how to:"}),(0,a.jsx)(i.A,{items:["Use a AI Research Prompt template to analyze lead data and generate personalized emails","Create new fields that indicate company research, personalized subject lines, and more","Use AI Research Prompt data as dynamic variables in your email templates","Preview and refine messages before sending","And more!"],color:"purple"})]}),transcript:`So now we've had Research go get new data and attach it to our lead records. Then it researched them as well — the contacts and companies.

But Research can do a lot more.

Research can take the Apollo data, the new data, and everything you put in the AI content center — those details about what you sell, your company, and the type of customers you're looking for — and write amazing personalized emails for us as well.

I've been able to remove the leads I don't want to focus on right now. I've also had it look to see if any of these contacts are active on LinkedIn. The ones that are, I'm going to treat a little differently. I want to start with manual posting in my sequence. But the ones that aren't, I want to have the Research write an amazing personalized email using all that information.

So let's finish strong. We're going to go back into Apollo. We're going to go to our list of leads — the ones we're using for Research. We'll select another built-by-Apollo Research in the “Generate a Message” category. Then I'll hop into my sequences to show you how I'm going to use that Research to send great personalized, automated emails to the right leads.

So you hop into your Apollo account. I'm going to hop into mine. Let's do it together.

Time for us to do our third and final Research for this course. Feel free to use the leads we've been using all along for this course. If you want to grab ten new ones, though, this would be a good time to do that. I'm going to keep using the ones I put into my list.

Let's go up to that Research button. We're going to start with a template. Next, you'll click Generate Message. You'll see multiple options created by Apollo. Now, these are multi-step Research. Whatever they say they're going to do, they'll go get that information, use it along with the Apollo data, and generate fantastic personalized emails. You'll notice you can have it research their professional posts, job openings, and what's happening at the company — then integrate that into what it's writing about.

I'm going to Write an email based on company priorities right here. You'll notice it's got four steps: it'll identify the company's priorities, research that account, write the personalized email, and even write a personalized subject line.

Once again, you'll be able to see a preview for all four steps with a couple of your leads right here to the left of the breakdown.

It might take a moment to populate that preview, especially when it's multiple steps. But once you check things out and it looks good, let's hit Save and Run.

That'll start your Research cascading through all the steps involved with that Research, and it'll start generating that information right on the record. Once your Research is done, you'll see that information start to populate in new fields created on those records — in this case, four of them for that one Research.

It was using the information on the record plus what we put into the AI content center to:

- Identify priority indicators (whether a company would be a good fit or not).

- Research the company.

- Put together a personalized email.

- Write a personalized subject line based on the information it found.

Now I'm going to pop over to a sequence I've already created for these types of leads. I've got step one with a manual email. I had a template in there. Normally, I'd personalize it from there, but I'm going to edit this one.

Of course, all that information from your Research is stored on the record. That means you can use them as dynamic variables.

So I'm going to leave this manual email for now as I'm just getting started with Research. I want to hit send. I want to read these and check them out before they go out. I'm still going to place the dynamic variables in here.

You'll notice that it will populate some of the recently created fields right at the bottom here, such as Write a Personalized Subject Line. I'll pop that in there. Then I'm going to pop in my personalized email dynamic variable as well.

Of course, you can find all your dynamic variables — including the ones created by your Research — by hitting the Add Dynamic Variables button. You'll see Recently Created right at the top, or you can scroll down or search for any others you might be looking for.

Now, the preview window here is showing a broken variable. It's in red. That means it can't find that information because I haven't selected a contact. You can hit the drop-down here. Just type the name of any of the leads from your list, and you'll see it pull up the personalized email from your Research right in the preview window.

Congrats! That's the end of this course.

You've seen how to use Research to improve your targeting, research your leads, and generate amazing personalized messaging as well. But with Research and custom prompting, there's no limit to what you can do to improve your sales process.

So thank you for joining me. Good luck, and happy selling!
